08:37.503 --> 08:42.336
[SPEAKER_92]: By 1895, both the park and its boathouse at Echo Park Lake were completed.

08:42.376 --> 08:53.385
[SPEAKER_92]: In the late 1910s, the area grew in prominence when it became a popular filming location for early motion picture companies along Alessandro Street, today known as Glendale Boulevard.

08:53.365 --> 09:06.062
[SPEAKER_92]: That connection to the film industry reflects the broader legacy of Hollywood, whose influence continues today as Los Angeles prepares for major global events like the 2026 FIFA World Cup and the 2028 Summer Olympics.

09:06.583 --> 09:19.120
[SPEAKER_92]: Construction is currently underway at the Los Angeles Convention Center, while new city legislation aims to keep film and television production in Los Angeles and preserve Hollywood's historic role as the heart of the movie industry.

09:20.281 --> 09:22.024
[SPEAKER_27]: Let's go to the movies.

09:22.044 --> 09:25.169
[SPEAKER_27]: The greatest medium for entertainment the world has ever known.

09:25.449 --> 09:28.574
[SPEAKER_27]: To most people, the movies in their theaters mean Hollywood.

09:28.995 --> 09:39.972
[SPEAKER_27]: Hollywood, California, USA, where 30,000 specialists working in 272 separate arts and crafts, sciences and trades, make the movies.

09:39.992 --> 09:43.217
[SPEAKER_27]: Working as a team to put their ideas into pictures.

09:48.597 --> 09:50.643
[SPEAKER_96]: What a day in Los Angeles, huh?

09:50.663 --> 09:57.645
[SPEAKER_96]: Today, the city of LA moved forward a series of motions that were designed to streamline the process of producing projects here in LA County.

09:59.482 --> 10:03.306
[SPEAKER_96]: Film work has been moving out of the city, out of the state, out of the country for a long time.

10:03.586 --> 10:06.209
[SPEAKER_96]: And we're trying to work to bring work back to this town.

10:06.809 --> 10:13.336
[SPEAKER_96]: We have an entire dedicated labor pool here in LA County that is bred and born to make movies, make art, make entertainment.

10:13.736 --> 10:15.037
[SPEAKER_96]: And right now, they're struggling.

10:15.218 --> 10:16.219
[SPEAKER_96]: Those jobs have gone away.

10:16.479 --> 10:20.303
[SPEAKER_96]: They're having trouble paying their rent, paying for health care, paying for basic necessities.

10:20.663 --> 10:28.611
[SPEAKER_96]: And so what the council did today was try to advance a series of motions that are going to bring that work back and start bringing stability back to the film industry in LA County.

10:28.591 --> 10:38.383
[SPEAKER_70]: Los Angeles is not clinging to outdated systems, and we are not surrendering our signature industry without a fight.

10:38.984 --> 10:55.045
[SPEAKER_70]: This offers hope to people who have been displaced, who have been looking for work, who used to be very busy maybe 10 years ago, a decade ago, or even five years ago, and their phone has stopped ringing, and they're on the cusp or verge of losing their insurance.

10:55.585 --> 10:57.788
[SPEAKER_70]: This, these measures,

10:57.768 --> 11:07.602
[SPEAKER_70]: are not going to turn the industry around right away, but they are letting the industry know Los Angeles is serious about making it easy to film here.

11:08.063 --> 11:09.645
[SPEAKER_70]: We want to keep the jobs here.

11:09.705 --> 11:12.910
[SPEAKER_70]: We want to make sure film shooting happens here.

11:14.052 --> 11:15.574
[SPEAKER_34]: We want those jobs back here.

11:15.614 --> 11:22.103
[SPEAKER_34]: This is the backbone of the entertainment industry, and it should be here in Los Angeles, in Hollywood.

11:22.123 --> 11:23.145
[SPEAKER_34]: Well, imagine it's made.

11:26.349 --> 11:27.471
[SPEAKER_70]: Mr. Nazarian.

11:28.328 --> 11:29.390
[SPEAKER_70]: Thank you, Council President.

11:29.531 --> 11:43.401
[SPEAKER_70]: I just wanted to say, first of all, thank you to everyone that's here, everyone from the bona fide film nerd to everyone who has come and spoken about their experiences.

11:43.381 --> 11:52.485
[SPEAKER_70]: the impact that this industry has had on their lives and or the impact it is now having on potentially breaking up their families.

11:52.545 --> 12:00.445
[SPEAKER_70]: These are the stories that have culminated into these set of seven motions that we're voting on today.

12:02.028 --> 12:03.791
[SPEAKER_70]: We can't afford complacency.

12:03.891 --> 12:09.180
[SPEAKER_70]: This industry sustains tens of thousands of working-class jobs.

12:09.501 --> 12:12.806
[SPEAKER_70]: This is the finish line for only phase one.

12:13.628 --> 12:14.569
[SPEAKER_70]: Let's not hesitate.

12:14.709 --> 12:15.350
[SPEAKER_70]: Let's act.

12:15.371 --> 12:16.693
[SPEAKER_70]: Let's keep Hollywood home.

12:17.634 --> 12:19.477
[SPEAKER_70]: I respectfully ask for your aye vote.

12:19.698 --> 12:20.018
[SPEAKER_70]: Thank you.

12:20.058 --> 12:22.382
[SPEAKER_76]: With that, let's open the roll on this item.

12:23.124 --> 12:23.825
[SPEAKER_76]: Close the roll.

