21:59.697 --> 22:01.779
[SPEAKER_32]: I started off as youth in Skid Row at 17.

22:02.400 --> 22:06.704
[SPEAKER_32]: My mom asked me to sleep with her boyfriend for rent money.

22:07.224 --> 22:08.706
[SPEAKER_32]: I decided to say no and I left.

22:09.386 --> 22:10.948
[SPEAKER_32]: I winded up in Skid Row.

22:15.282 --> 22:24.011
[SPEAKER_32]: We're here today at a panel hosted by Social Model Recovery Systems to share my lived experience of being a youth in Skid Row.

22:24.651 --> 22:27.494
[SPEAKER_45]: Our work started in Skid Row in 1996.

22:28.135 --> 22:32.720
[SPEAKER_45]: The work that we're celebrating today is just the impact of our work with youth in Skid Row.

22:34.201 --> 22:40.007
[SPEAKER_37]: Everybody just went like this and didn't pay attention to these beautiful people.

22:40.477 --> 22:42.461
[SPEAKER_32]: Being in Skid Row was really hard.

22:42.582 --> 22:50.439
[SPEAKER_32]: I stayed in a tent or I would be at Lafayette Park playing basketball until like 2, 3 o'clock in the morning and then going to school at 8.

22:51.200 --> 22:55.770
[SPEAKER_32]: Playing sports in Skid Row like at Gladys Park helped me like cope throughout the day.

22:56.231 --> 23:00.240
[SPEAKER_32]: I was able to finish my homework a lot of times inside the park.

23:00.457 --> 23:05.082
[SPEAKER_37]: The kids in this community taught us where we live is not safe.

23:05.583 --> 23:06.264
[SPEAKER_37]: We need help.

23:06.804 --> 23:15.835
[SPEAKER_32]: I would try to stay away from individuals who would offer me money to sleep with them or offer me alcohol.

23:15.875 --> 23:18.438
[SPEAKER_32]: And they would say, oh, take this, and it'll make you feel warm.

23:19.099 --> 23:20.580
[SPEAKER_32]: You won't have to be so cold at night.

23:21.521 --> 23:26.447
[SPEAKER_32]: I decided to continue to say no, and then I was homeless for five years.

23:27.001 --> 23:30.667
[SPEAKER_45]: Our work is really grounded in looking at what makes a healthy community?

23:30.968 --> 23:34.854
[SPEAKER_45]: What is it that people need in their neighborhood to thrive and to be successful?

23:35.235 --> 23:40.324
[SPEAKER_32]: I got connected to Social Monitoring Recovery Systems Prevention Program by another youth.

23:41.085 --> 23:44.050
[SPEAKER_32]: They shared with me housing opportunities and shelters.

23:44.651 --> 23:52.384
[SPEAKER_32]: I can't express how much their work has affected me in becoming a college graduate today.

23:52.364 --> 23:59.792
[SPEAKER_42]: Without stable housing and the support that goes along with stable housing, it's impossible to live to your full potential.

24:00.072 --> 24:06.960
