[SPEAKER_52]: Elections have consequences.

01:21:23.332 --> 01:21:33.208
[SPEAKER_52]: So when Richard was able to not only win in 94, but also win in 96, 96 was critical because by that time, Assembly Democrats lost the House.

01:21:34.270 --> 01:21:38.577
[SPEAKER_52]: We were controlled by Republicans and it took Richard Polanco to bring back

01:21:39.215 --> 01:21:45.110
[SPEAKER_52]: the assembly to the Democratic column, because Willie lost the House in 94.

01:21:45.150 --> 01:21:47.456
[SPEAKER_52]: Of course, Willie doesn't say that too loud, but I do.

01:21:48.178 --> 01:21:50.263
[SPEAKER_52]: And who's keeping score?

01:21:51.366 --> 01:21:53.492
[SPEAKER_52]: Richard never keeps score, but I do.

01:21:54.294 --> 01:21:55.637
[SPEAKER_52]: I do.

01:21:56.630 --> 01:21:58.993
[SPEAKER_52]: I do, ni modo, you know.

01:21:59.634 --> 01:22:07.004
[SPEAKER_52]: So that year, 96 was watershed for Latino Caucus because we elected the first Latino speaker, Cruz Bustamante.

01:22:07.024 --> 01:22:10.449
[SPEAKER_52]: We elected the first Latino majority leader, Antonio Villaraigosa.

01:22:10.830 --> 01:22:18.300
[SPEAKER_52]: We elected the first chair of the Budget Committee, Latina, Denise Moreno-Tuschini from Barrio Logan in San Diego, Barrio Logan.

01:22:18.280 --> 01:22:24.785
[SPEAKER_52]: And we elected the first chair, the first woman Latina to chair the Judicial Committee ever in the history of California.

01:22:25.066 --> 01:22:28.881
[SPEAKER_52]: From East L.A., yours truly, Marta Escutia.

01:22:31.662 --> 01:22:41.661
[SPEAKER_52]: So the impact of all that was that in 1997, we had to stop the budget for one thing, food stamps for legal immigrants.

01:22:42.362 --> 01:22:46.389
[SPEAKER_52]: Can you believe it that we had to fight for food stamps for legal immigrants?

01:22:46.970 --> 01:22:48.253
[SPEAKER_52]: And you know who we had to fight?

01:22:48.734 --> 01:22:49.796
[SPEAKER_52]: Not the Republicans.

01:22:50.116 --> 01:22:53.282
[SPEAKER_52]: We had to fight our own Democrats in the Democratic caucus.

01:22:53.262 --> 01:22:57.266
[SPEAKER_52]: So what did Richard Polanco and I and Denise and Antonio, we all did?

01:22:57.687 --> 01:23:10.501
[SPEAKER_52]: We hid and we prevented a quorum so that the decision could not be made and it gave time for Bustamante and Pete Wilson to negotiate the food stamps and Pete agreed.

01:23:10.561 --> 01:23:12.964
[SPEAKER_52]: We just had to ask him and he agreed.

01:23:13.024 --> 01:23:21.413
[SPEAKER_52]: So I tell that story because many times our opponents are our own allegedly allies.

01:23:21.882 --> 01:23:25.906
[SPEAKER_52]: We have to fight our own Democrats to get things done for our own community.

01:23:26.547 --> 01:23:35.296
[SPEAKER_52]: I can't believe still to this moment that we had to negotiate morality because there is something very immoral about negotiating food stamps for poor people.

01:23:35.977 --> 01:23:39.040
[SPEAKER_52]: That to me is a non-issue, should never be on the table.

01:23:39.660 --> 01:23:43.484
[SPEAKER_52]: But we did it because we had the power and we did it because Richard had a vision.

01:23:44.345 --> 01:23:46.928
[SPEAKER_52]: And so many times it takes

01:23:46.908 --> 01:23:52.855
[SPEAKER_52]: an extraordinary person to deliver extraordinary effort to do very ordinary things.

01:23:53.636 --> 01:23:58.742
[SPEAKER_52]: A food stamp is something very ordinary, but to that person it means a lot, you know.

01:23:58.862 --> 01:24:14.940
[SPEAKER_52]: And it was Richard who crisscrossed the state, literally crisscrossed the state in his car, finding people, recruiting candidates, promising them that he would not only, you know, endorse them, but also not leave them alone and follow up with,

01:24:15.173 --> 01:24:20.742
[SPEAKER_52]: with what we need, which is, you know, fundraising efforts from somebody who was very good at that.

01:24:21.503 --> 01:24:27.632
[SPEAKER_52]: And Richard went beyond and above that, because for Richard, he was not looking for political transactions.

01:24:28.313 --> 01:24:33.361
[SPEAKER_52]: Richard was looking for relationships, relationships based on the shared values that we all share.

01:24:34.102 --> 01:24:41.974
[SPEAKER_52]: So that's the Richard Polanco that I know, that's the Richard Polanco that I respect, and that's the Richard Polanco that I love.

01:24:41.954 --> 01:24:50.013
[SPEAKER_52]: I am deeply grateful to you, Councilwoman Hernandez, for recognizing a man that many times does not get the recognition that he deserves.

01:24:51.075 --> 01:25:00.216
[SPEAKER_52]: I thank the body and I thank the Council President for allowing us the time to honor this man the way he should be honored.

01:25:00.196 --> 01:25:13.118
[SPEAKER_52]: Libby, Gabriel, Liana, Richard Jr., your grandchildren, I thank you for giving us Richard during those very formative years and very turbulent years of Latino empowerment.

01:25:13.719 --> 01:25:19.149
[SPEAKER_52]: If it wouldn't have been for the family backing him up, I don't think, we wouldn't be here, Libby, so thank you.

01:25:19.890 --> 01:25:21.613
[SPEAKER_52]: Thank you, Libby.

01:25:25.171 --> 01:25:32.339
[SPEAKER_52]: And Richard, desde la profundidad de mi corazón, muchísimas gracias por todo lo que has hecho por nuestra comunidad.

01:25:32.739 --> 01:25:36.403
[SPEAKER_52]: From the bottom of my heart, thank you very much for all you've done for our community.

01:25:37.324 --> 01:25:38.966
[SPEAKER_52]: Gracias, yo también puedo traducir.

01:25:40.347 --> 01:25:44.051
[SPEAKER_52]: But I thank you so much for everything that you have done for all of us.

01:25:44.552 --> 01:25:52.220
[SPEAKER_52]: I don't think there's enough time in this limited time that we have in this earth to really thank you for everything that you have done for the community, Richard.

01:25:52.600 --> 01:25:53.541
[SPEAKER_52]: Thank you so much.

01:26:01.992 --> 01:26:05.482
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you, thank you, Senator Escutia for joining us today.

01:26:05.542 --> 01:26:13.385
[SPEAKER_36]: Now we are gonna have a titan of the labor movement, State Senator, Marielena Durazo, share a few words with us.

01:26:13.526 --> 01:26:15.090
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you.

01:26:18.344 --> 01:26:18.845
[SPEAKER_41]: Thank you.

01:26:18.865 --> 01:26:22.048
[SPEAKER_41]: Good morning, council members and community.

01:26:22.589 --> 01:26:25.212
[SPEAKER_41]: And thank you, Councilwoman Hernandez.

01:26:25.692 --> 01:26:39.288
[SPEAKER_41]: It is an honor to be with all of you here today in the City Council to celebrate a remarkable leader, a dear friend, and a true champion for our communities, Senator Richard Polanco.

01:26:44.534 --> 01:26:48.098
[SPEAKER_41]: I met Richard through my husband, Miguel.

01:26:48.803 --> 01:26:53.129
[SPEAKER_41]: through Miguel, as you all know, was really brilliant about politics.

01:26:54.051 --> 01:27:04.886
[SPEAKER_41]: He was, you know, friends with Richard through the Farm Workers Union, through being out there in East L.A. and doing voter registration, the real work, the really hard work.

01:27:05.247 --> 01:27:08.331
[SPEAKER_41]: People didn't get the ballot in the mail.

01:27:09.239 --> 01:27:11.162
[SPEAKER_41]: You know, they didn't get the voter registration.

01:27:11.362 --> 01:27:14.807
[SPEAKER_41]: It was hard, hard work, one by one by one.

01:27:15.328 --> 01:27:28.426
[SPEAKER_41]: And I'm so grateful as the newly elected head of the Hotel and Restaurant Workers Union that I had a friend in politics, that I had a friend who believed in hardworking people and poor people.

01:27:28.867 --> 01:27:34.234
[SPEAKER_41]: He's part of a generation of leaders who changed the face of California politics.

01:27:34.214 --> 01:27:50.620
[SPEAKER_41]: As my dear friend Martha Escudia said, Assemblymember Richard Alatorre developed the master plan to create legislative districts where Latino communities would finally have the opportunity to elect representatives who reflected our community.

01:27:51.697 --> 01:27:57.711
[SPEAKER_41]: When Richard Polanco was elected to the Assembly in 86, he took that vision and he turned it into reality.

01:27:58.092 --> 01:28:06.972
[SPEAKER_41]: He helped create one of the most important institutions in state government, the California Latino Legislative Caucus.

01:28:07.407 --> 01:28:13.272
[SPEAKER_41]: But Richard's legacy is not only about representation, it is also about justice.

01:28:13.713 --> 01:28:27.825
[SPEAKER_41]: Throughout his career, everywhere he went, to this day, he stood firmly with working people, with immigrants, with labor, with farm workers, and with women, with you just name it, he was always there.

01:28:27.945 --> 01:28:35.953
[SPEAKER_41]: To this day, we are together fighting for something as simple as internet and connectivity for everyone.

01:28:36.133 --> 01:28:37.414
[SPEAKER_41]: Think about that.

01:28:37.394 --> 01:28:41.501
[SPEAKER_41]: To this day, Richard always led with courage.

01:28:41.942 --> 01:28:44.967
[SPEAKER_41]: A lot of people have power, but they don't have courage.

01:28:45.347 --> 01:28:47.571
[SPEAKER_41]: He always has courage.

01:28:48.272 --> 01:28:53.361
[SPEAKER_41]: There's an old sexist saying that behind every great man is a good woman.

01:28:54.438 --> 01:29:00.884
[SPEAKER_41]: Richard Polanco built the modern California Latino Caucus by flipping that old saying on its head.

01:29:01.564 --> 01:29:09.591
[SPEAKER_41]: Richard recognized that by supporting Latinas, we could capitalize on the women's movement and break out of the barrios.

01:29:09.611 --> 01:29:23.483
[SPEAKER_41]: In the early 90s, he backed Martha Scutia, Liz Figueroa, Deborah Ortiz, Diane Martinez, Denise Ducheney, Grace Napolitano, Hilda Solis.

01:29:23.463 --> 01:29:27.369
[SPEAKER_41]: Jenny Oropesa, Sally Havis, and Nel Soto.

01:29:27.950 --> 01:29:33.799
[SPEAKER_41]: He brought the meaning of Si Se Puede into the lives of Latinas in politics.

01:29:34.299 --> 01:29:39.868
[SPEAKER_41]: Today, I am just one of the 22 Latinas serving in the state legislature.

01:29:40.389 --> 01:29:44.695
[SPEAKER_41]: He has been a good man behind some great women.

01:29:52.083 --> 01:29:59.533
[SPEAKER_41]: Just as he welcomed us, let us now welcome him today as we celebrate his 75th birthday.

01:29:59.994 --> 01:30:06.502
[SPEAKER_41]: Richard, on behalf of the California State Senate, my honor to present this resolution to you.

01:30:18.599 --> 01:30:18.799
[SPEAKER_60]: Thank you.

01:30:19.589 --> 01:30:29.249
[SPEAKER_60]: Thank you, Senator.

01:30:29.289 --> 01:30:34.700
[SPEAKER_36]: Now it is my pleasure to welcome and introduce former state senator and city council member Richard Alarcon.

01:30:34.780 --> 01:30:35.562
[SPEAKER_36]: Share a few words with us.

01:30:35.602 --> 01:30:36.163
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you.

01:30:46.775 --> 01:30:52.426
[SPEAKER_67]: First of all, having to, having to speak after these two incredible women is a, is a task indeed.

01:30:52.566 --> 01:30:58.277
[SPEAKER_67]: But, uh, we are here because Richard Polanco deserves to be recognized.

01:30:59.159 --> 01:31:00.141
[SPEAKER_67]: Not for him personally.

01:31:00.241 --> 01:31:05.070
[SPEAKER_67]: He has plenty of recognitions hanging on his walls, wherever he puts his recognitions.

01:31:05.776 --> 01:31:07.919
[SPEAKER_67]: but they're all well-deserved.

01:31:08.039 --> 01:31:18.152
[SPEAKER_67]: I don't want to go through the litany of things because it's impossible in just one day to explain all the things that Richard has done legislatively.

01:31:19.133 --> 01:31:34.753
[SPEAKER_67]: But I do want to mention that the reason so many elected officials throughout the state of California on school boards, on water districts, on you name it, there are probably thousands of elected officials who benefited from

01:31:34.733 --> 01:31:40.280
[SPEAKER_67]: California Voting Rights Act, excuse me.

01:31:42.903 --> 01:31:56.860
[SPEAKER_67]: Because these jurisdictions did not have district-wide elections, they had general elections which excluded minorities, not just Latinos, but minorities from being elected in their communities.

01:31:56.992 --> 01:31:59.415
[SPEAKER_67]: And so we stand on his shoulders.

01:31:59.476 --> 01:32:03.882
[SPEAKER_67]: But I want to talk about Richard, the guy that fought for me.

01:32:04.523 --> 01:32:07.387
[SPEAKER_67]: And that was when I was in a race for state senate.

01:32:08.148 --> 01:32:14.216
[SPEAKER_67]: And at 11 o'clock on election night, I was losing by 600 votes.

01:32:15.498 --> 01:32:21.767
[SPEAKER_67]: And even my staff left the little restaurant we were at.

01:32:22.591 --> 01:32:31.464
[SPEAKER_67]: There were like three people there, and fortunately I was paying my campaign manager, so they were there.

01:32:32.105 --> 01:32:36.552
[SPEAKER_67]: But at 12 o'clock, I was losing by 400 votes.

01:32:37.393 --> 01:32:40.618
[SPEAKER_67]: At one o'clock, I was losing by 300 votes.

01:32:41.820 --> 01:32:51.214
[SPEAKER_67]: Okay, I could be off a vote or two, but the bottom line is Richard stayed the whole time, praying, praying.

01:32:53.236 --> 01:32:59.136
[SPEAKER_67]: Yes, to baby Jesus, praying for him to pull us through.

01:32:59.157 --> 01:33:04.495
[SPEAKER_67]: At three o'clock, as you all know, I won by 29 votes.

01:33:05.403 --> 01:33:10.107
[SPEAKER_67]: It was the closest race in California history at the time.

01:33:10.607 --> 01:33:20.436
[SPEAKER_67]: But the point I'm trying to make is, Richard, with those thousands of people that he's helped get elected, he's not just there in numerical counts.

01:33:20.496 --> 01:33:22.758
[SPEAKER_67]: He's not just there to do publicity.

01:33:23.338 --> 01:33:27.662
[SPEAKER_67]: He's there behind the scenes becoming their friend, becoming their advocate.

01:33:28.282 --> 01:33:29.844
[SPEAKER_67]: And finally, just let me say this.

01:33:30.424 --> 01:33:34.768
[SPEAKER_67]: Whatever you think about political stalwarts,

01:33:35.727 --> 01:33:41.338
[SPEAKER_67]: Richard never asked me to change my opinion on a vote.

01:33:42.200 --> 01:33:51.740
[SPEAKER_67]: He always let whoever got elected under his wing, he always let them do what they needed to do as an individual.

01:33:52.762 --> 01:33:54.445
[SPEAKER_67]: And that's the strength.

01:33:55.049 --> 01:33:56.210
[SPEAKER_67]: of Richard Polanco.

01:33:56.270 --> 01:34:06.302
[SPEAKER_67]: That's why he continued to build, because his loyalty generated a return loyalty from all these people here and hundreds and hundreds more.

01:34:07.002 --> 01:34:15.091
[SPEAKER_67]: So we're here to celebrate, I believe, one of the most incredible politicians in the history of California.

01:34:15.752 --> 01:34:20.938
[SPEAKER_67]: I'll tell you something, the Energizer bunny has nothing on this guy.

01:34:21.475 --> 01:34:27.068
[SPEAKER_67]: And so we are so gracious to have the opportunity to speak before this council.

01:34:27.148 --> 01:34:28.632
[SPEAKER_67]: Of course, Tony and I served here.

01:34:29.273 --> 01:34:36.530
[SPEAKER_67]: And so we are just honored to be here to tell you what a great man we had the pleasure to know and work with.

01:34:36.550 --> 01:34:37.071
[SPEAKER_67]: Thank you.

01:34:43.025 --> 01:34:43.526
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you.

01:34:43.546 --> 01:34:45.050
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you, Richard.

01:34:45.131 --> 01:34:51.808
[SPEAKER_36]: Finally, before we hear from the man of the hour, please welcome former Congress member, city council member, Tony Cardenas to share a few words with us.

01:34:51.829 --> 01:34:52.410
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you.

01:34:56.204 --> 01:34:59.110
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Councilwoman, Councilmembers, and Council President.

01:34:59.671 --> 01:35:04.161
[SPEAKER_08]: This is truly an honor to have a few moments to speak about this great, great man.

01:35:05.543 --> 01:35:13.099
[SPEAKER_08]: The first person who ever endorsed me when I decided to run for office was State Senator Richard Polanco.

01:35:13.079 --> 01:35:17.488
[SPEAKER_08]: And yes, and every moment with him was like going to school.

01:35:19.132 --> 01:35:23.080
[SPEAKER_08]: Some people don't realize it, but rabbi means teacher, and he is my rabbi.

01:35:23.320 --> 01:35:24.162
[SPEAKER_08]: He is my teacher.

01:35:24.844 --> 01:35:30.295
[SPEAKER_08]: I was fortunate to get to Sacramento after winning that race, and we had

01:35:30.798 --> 01:35:37.765
[SPEAKER_08]: literally on the docks where the United States Postal Service would not deliver that mail until they got the cashier's check.

01:35:38.225 --> 01:35:46.674
[SPEAKER_08]: We literally had bags and bags of mail on the docks, and the only person that was in the position to help me was Senator Richard Polanco.

01:35:46.974 --> 01:35:56.704
[SPEAKER_08]: With one phone call, we explained to him how much money we needed, and he sent Bill Mabee with a cashier's check to my campaign the following morning, and we won that race.

01:35:59.941 --> 01:36:03.506
[SPEAKER_08]: When I got to Sacramento, I didn't even have a place to stay.

01:36:04.047 --> 01:36:10.477
[SPEAKER_08]: So I slept on the couch of Richard Polanco and then speaker Cruz Dustamante.

01:36:11.078 --> 01:36:15.885
[SPEAKER_08]: And the thing about it is I didn't realize that they just wanted to have somebody to make fun of.

01:36:16.766 --> 01:36:19.651
[SPEAKER_08]: Because I was new to politics and they were veteranos.

01:36:19.671 --> 01:36:20.953
[SPEAKER_08]: They really knew what they were doing.

01:36:20.973 --> 01:36:28.564
[SPEAKER_08]: So every night they would open up a bottle of wine and I didn't know the difference between ripple or duck corn or anything back then.

01:36:29.168 --> 01:36:30.951
[SPEAKER_08]: Because of him, I do know the difference.

01:36:31.932 --> 01:36:34.156
[SPEAKER_08]: But literally, they would ask me questions.

01:36:34.557 --> 01:36:36.339
[SPEAKER_08]: These veteranos would ask me questions.

01:36:36.820 --> 01:36:37.762
[SPEAKER_08]: And then they would laugh.

01:36:37.862 --> 01:36:40.386
[SPEAKER_08]: And they would say, this guy doesn't know what happened in committee today.

01:36:40.746 --> 01:36:41.828
[SPEAKER_08]: Because I would tell them the answer.

01:36:41.848 --> 01:36:42.970
[SPEAKER_08]: And they said, no, that's not what happened.

01:36:42.990 --> 01:36:43.831
[SPEAKER_08]: And they would school me.

01:36:43.851 --> 01:36:44.693
[SPEAKER_08]: They would teach me.

01:36:45.173 --> 01:36:52.725
[SPEAKER_08]: I tell all of you that because there's somebody in your life, somebody who is more experienced than you, somebody who's been there, done that.

01:36:53.126 --> 01:36:57.032
[SPEAKER_08]: And if they afford the time to offer you their wisdom,

01:36:57.012 --> 01:37:03.521
[SPEAKER_08]: Please, please, please take it, because they will tell you the mistakes that they made so that you don't have to make them.

01:37:04.061 --> 01:37:09.989
[SPEAKER_08]: They will help you understand and read between the lines so that you understand how to do it for yourself.

01:37:10.550 --> 01:37:14.195
[SPEAKER_08]: That is what I learned from this man, and that's what I appreciate about him.

01:37:14.275 --> 01:37:15.456
[SPEAKER_08]: And that's not the only thing.

01:37:15.857 --> 01:37:22.986
[SPEAKER_08]: So when I got elected, I went from the state legislature to the city council and to Washington, always with this man's support.

01:37:22.966 --> 01:37:29.214
[SPEAKER_08]: And when I got to Washington, I got there, and I said something along the lines of what Richard Polanco said when he got to Sacramento.

01:37:29.575 --> 01:37:31.678
[SPEAKER_08]: He said, there's not enough Latinos here.

01:37:32.619 --> 01:37:35.323
[SPEAKER_08]: When I got to Washington, I said, there's not enough Latinos here.

01:37:35.943 --> 01:37:42.032
[SPEAKER_08]: So I vied to be the chairman of the committee that elects Latinos on behalf of the Hispanic Caucus.

01:37:42.673 --> 01:37:46.037
[SPEAKER_08]: And they elected me.

01:37:47.047 --> 01:37:54.356
[SPEAKER_08]: They elected me, and I made some lofty promises, but I knew in the back of my mind by channeling Richard Polanco and what he taught me, I could make it happen.

01:37:55.297 --> 01:38:00.604
[SPEAKER_08]: The Hispanic caucus had never been able to raise a million dollars or more in an election cycle.

01:38:01.365 --> 01:38:03.988
[SPEAKER_08]: And I was crazy enough to say, we're going to raise three million or more.

01:38:04.189 --> 01:38:07.052
[SPEAKER_08]: And people literally laughed at me, but they voted for me anyway.

01:38:07.072 --> 01:38:08.995
[SPEAKER_08]: This young man's got crazy energy.

01:38:09.015 --> 01:38:09.876
[SPEAKER_08]: He doesn't know what he's doing.

01:38:09.896 --> 01:38:12.379
[SPEAKER_08]: He's a freshman, but hey, I like his energy.

01:38:12.359 --> 01:38:14.184
[SPEAKER_08]: So they elected me to be their chairman.

01:38:14.364 --> 01:38:23.648
[SPEAKER_08]: We raised $6 million in the first term, and then an additional $11 million in the next term, and then another $18 million in the next term.

01:38:24.049 --> 01:38:29.423
[SPEAKER_08]: And we went from 25 members of the Hispanic caucus to 43 in just six years.

01:38:30.905 --> 01:38:32.406
[SPEAKER_08]: But that is what he did.

01:38:32.467 --> 01:38:35.369
[SPEAKER_08]: That is what this man did in Sacramento.

01:38:36.110 --> 01:38:40.194
[SPEAKER_08]: He more than doubled and tripled the number of Hispanics since the day he got there.

01:38:40.795 --> 01:38:42.336
[SPEAKER_08]: He is a rabbi.

01:38:42.536 --> 01:38:44.678
[SPEAKER_08]: He is a teacher of the best kind.

01:38:44.979 --> 01:38:46.520
[SPEAKER_08]: And there's something else I'm gonna tell you.

01:38:46.580 --> 01:38:50.104
[SPEAKER_08]: People think that he only helped Latinos and Latinas get elected.

01:38:50.584 --> 01:38:59.713
[SPEAKER_08]: There's a person who is now, well, there's two people who helped get elected, who are now the United States Senators of California, Senator Alex Padilla and Senator Adam Schiff.

01:39:01.516 --> 01:39:11.694
[SPEAKER_08]: Richard Polanco was the one who recruited Adam Schiff to run for the State Senate, and Richard Polanco muscled that good man into office, and he was grateful.

01:39:11.954 --> 01:39:16.823
[SPEAKER_08]: But there was not a quid pro quo, as was said earlier by Richard Alarcon.

01:39:16.843 --> 01:39:24.216
[SPEAKER_08]: There was not a quid pro quo, because when Richard Polanco ran for pro tem of the State Senate, he did not get the commitment

01:39:25.208 --> 01:39:28.772
[SPEAKER_08]: of State Senator Adam Schiff at the time to vote for him for pro temp.

01:39:29.053 --> 01:39:30.454
[SPEAKER_08]: You know why he didn't get the commitment?

01:39:30.634 --> 01:39:32.056
[SPEAKER_08]: Because it was not a condition.

01:39:32.937 --> 01:39:35.200
[SPEAKER_08]: And that is one of the things that I want to set straight here.

01:39:36.481 --> 01:39:44.291
[SPEAKER_08]: Especially when it comes to elected officials of color, people assume that we don't have integrity.

01:39:44.951 --> 01:39:47.975
[SPEAKER_08]: People assume that we work on quid pro quos.

01:39:47.995 --> 01:39:49.697
[SPEAKER_08]: And that is just not the case.

01:39:54.622 --> 01:40:03.743
[SPEAKER_08]: So when I got to Washington DC, immediately when I was able to do that for the Hispanic Caucus, I begged the Black Caucus to follow our lead.

01:40:04.163 --> 01:40:07.892
[SPEAKER_08]: I begged the Women's Caucus, who didn't even have a PAC at the time, to open a PAC.

01:40:08.213 --> 01:40:10.478
[SPEAKER_08]: I begged the Gay Caucus to do the same.

01:40:10.718 --> 01:40:12.883
[SPEAKER_08]: The Asian Caucus to do the same.

01:40:12.863 --> 01:40:13.864
[SPEAKER_08]: And you know what?

01:40:14.124 --> 01:40:15.126
[SPEAKER_08]: They finally listened.

01:40:15.426 --> 01:40:36.411
[SPEAKER_08]: And now, together, and I did the count, together, last cycle, together we raised over $50 million to elect people of our communities to Washington, D.C. And for the first time, people who run for President of the United States have to meet with the Hispanic Caucus if they want our endorsement.

01:40:36.631 --> 01:40:37.752
[SPEAKER_08]: That never happened.

01:40:38.173 --> 01:40:41.757
[SPEAKER_08]: That is true power, where it belongs.

01:40:42.479 --> 01:40:45.364
[SPEAKER_08]: I give you these examples not because I was a part of it.

01:40:45.624 --> 01:40:57.945
[SPEAKER_08]: I give you these examples because if I didn't have the teacher to teach me how to be empowered, how to understand my power, and how to follow my passion for improving the community for everyone, I would not have been able to do that.

01:40:57.966 --> 01:40:58.867
[SPEAKER_08]: And that is the truth.

01:40:59.248 --> 01:41:00.710
[SPEAKER_08]: That is the simple truth.

01:41:00.730 --> 01:41:05.759
[SPEAKER_08]: So I stand here grateful and honored to call this man my friend.

01:41:06.360 --> 01:41:08.183
[SPEAKER_08]: And even though back then,

01:41:08.315 --> 01:41:10.300
[SPEAKER_08]: I didn't used to say, I love you, Richard.

01:41:10.701 --> 01:41:12.445
[SPEAKER_08]: I will say it again before all of you.

01:41:13.067 --> 01:41:19.222
[SPEAKER_08]: Now that I'm a grandfather, now that I've learned how to say that more than ever, Richard, I love you, brother.

01:41:19.402 --> 01:41:21.447
[SPEAKER_08]: And thank you so much for being you.

01:41:32.767 --> 01:41:33.688
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you, Congressman.

01:41:34.108 --> 01:41:34.769
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you so much.

01:41:35.169 --> 01:41:41.995
[SPEAKER_36]: And before I pass it to the man of the hour, I want to make sure that we can recognize a few other titans and leaders that are here with us today.

01:41:42.035 --> 01:41:45.378
[SPEAKER_36]: We have retired Senator Dean Flores with us here today.

01:41:47.300 --> 01:41:50.663
[SPEAKER_36]: We have Congresswoman Lucille Roybal here with us today.

01:41:50.703 --> 01:41:56.729
[SPEAKER_36]: And retired Assemblyman Manny Gomez also joining us here today.

01:41:56.769 --> 01:41:58.050
[SPEAKER_36]: Manny Diaz, sorry.

01:41:58.450 --> 01:42:01.693
[SPEAKER_36]: Manny Diaz joining us here today.

01:42:02.483 --> 01:42:10.461
[SPEAKER_36]: And now it is my pleasure to introduce the man who taught us what it means to build true people power, what it looks like to build pipelines of leadership.

01:42:11.122 --> 01:42:14.991
[SPEAKER_36]: Please let's give a huge round of applause to welcome Senator Richard Blanco to the podium.

01:42:57.833 --> 01:43:03.219
[SPEAKER_72]: Mr. President, members of the Council, I want to thank you for the honor.

01:43:04.421 --> 01:43:11.729
[SPEAKER_72]: Estimado público, es un placer y un gran honor estar aquí con cada uno de ustedes.

01:43:13.411 --> 01:43:26.727
[SPEAKER_72]: Let me begin by acknowledging Senator Scutia, former Congress member Tony Cardenas, Senator Durazo, my former colleagues who are here,

01:43:27.382 --> 01:43:45.413
[SPEAKER_72]: Assemblymember Manny Diaz, Lucille Roybal-Allard, Dean Flores, and Papa Chulo, which is the nickname we gave to Senator Alarcón.

01:43:45.433 --> 01:43:50.080
[SPEAKER_72]: I'm one who believes and subscribes to the notion that no one makes it alone in this world.

01:43:50.681 --> 01:43:53.406
[SPEAKER_72]: At some point in our path,

01:43:53.622 --> 01:43:59.290
[SPEAKER_72]: We were touched by a teacher who saw more in us than we saw in ourselves.

01:43:59.951 --> 01:44:07.181
[SPEAKER_72]: We were touched and blessed with parents who provided, at times, worked two jobs.

01:44:08.243 --> 01:44:15.112
[SPEAKER_72]: We were blessed with opportunities that at that point in time growing up were limited.

01:44:15.793 --> 01:44:19.258
[SPEAKER_72]: But before I go further, let me introduce my family.

01:44:21.652 --> 01:44:28.763
[SPEAKER_72]: Let me begin by introducing the foundation, the rock, of the Polanco family.

01:44:28.783 --> 01:44:30.025
[SPEAKER_72]: A quick story.

01:44:30.946 --> 01:44:41.582
[SPEAKER_72]: When we met, we were both in a different relationship, and my wife was engaged.

01:44:43.104 --> 01:44:45.668
[SPEAKER_72]: They're laughing, but it's a great story because

01:44:53.849 --> 01:44:55.010
[SPEAKER_72]: Let me put it this way.

01:44:56.312 --> 01:44:59.415
[SPEAKER_72]: We ended up 47 years ago in marriage.

01:45:05.161 --> 01:45:08.345
[SPEAKER_72]: We celebrate this year our 48th.

01:45:09.886 --> 01:45:15.793
[SPEAKER_72]: And it's not about the woman behind or a spouse, a good partner.

01:45:17.054 --> 01:45:20.818
[SPEAKER_72]: They stand with you, next to you.

01:45:22.064 --> 01:45:22.865
[SPEAKER_72]: on that journey.

01:45:23.245 --> 01:45:27.690
[SPEAKER_72]: And so to my wife, Libby, thank you.

01:45:28.031 --> 01:45:31.835
[SPEAKER_72]: You're my partner, my soulmate, and te quiero mucho.

01:45:38.763 --> 01:45:43.468
[SPEAKER_72]: Let me introduce my siblings, the oldest, Richard Jr.

01:45:46.972 --> 01:45:49.995
[SPEAKER_72]: Excuse me, my children, my children.

01:45:51.528 --> 01:45:57.895
[SPEAKER_72]: He looks like my brother, so I'll introduce him as a brother.

01:45:58.636 --> 01:46:04.843
[SPEAKER_72]: No, my oldest son, Richard Jr., his son, my grandson, Rocco Polanco.

01:46:06.444 --> 01:46:09.808
[SPEAKER_72]: Also with us today is Gabriel.

01:46:11.110 --> 01:46:13.672
[SPEAKER_72]: Right here, his wife, Melissa.

01:46:14.133 --> 01:46:15.434
[SPEAKER_72]: My granddaughter, London.

01:46:16.295 --> 01:46:17.957
[SPEAKER_72]: My granddaughter, Berlin.

01:46:19.158 --> 01:46:20.640
[SPEAKER_72]: The joy of my life.

01:46:22.207 --> 01:46:28.713
[SPEAKER_72]: And the Jew, my precious one, Liana Polanco, my daughter.

01:46:29.134 --> 01:46:29.954
[SPEAKER_72]: Please welcome them.

01:46:33.978 --> 01:46:35.880
[SPEAKER_72]: I'm a little nervous, and I don't know why.

01:46:36.260 --> 01:46:37.682
[SPEAKER_72]: So I'm just going to put this away.

01:46:37.722 --> 01:46:39.263
[SPEAKER_72]: Thank you.

01:46:39.964 --> 01:46:43.187
[SPEAKER_72]: And be very, very short.

01:46:47.251 --> 01:46:50.374
[SPEAKER_72]: I got into politics because I believe that government

01:46:51.620 --> 01:46:54.464
[SPEAKER_72]: could make a difference in people's lives.

01:46:54.484 --> 01:47:01.474
[SPEAKER_72]: I grew up in a period of time when the 60s and 70s, our country was torn apart, much like we see today.

01:47:03.076 --> 01:47:07.582
[SPEAKER_72]: It was a time when US students were protesting.

01:47:08.844 --> 01:47:13.230
[SPEAKER_72]: Our military National Guard had killed students at Kent State.

01:47:13.731 --> 01:47:18.117
[SPEAKER_72]: There are a lot of parallels that are happening today that

01:47:18.316 --> 01:47:20.619
[SPEAKER_72]: I experienced, watched, and watched.

01:47:20.879 --> 01:47:31.590
[SPEAKER_72]: And so my way of being is based on a series of decades of events that occurred.

01:47:32.571 --> 01:47:44.104
[SPEAKER_72]: And so when I realized that we could either continue to do the marching and the protesting of which I participated, student walkouts, Chicano moratorium,

01:47:45.569 --> 01:47:52.018
[SPEAKER_72]: Or we can get into the system and make the system work for the benefit of people.

01:47:52.038 --> 01:48:08.202
[SPEAKER_72]: And I got to see how government, through the war on poverty, the great society, was able to invest money in making quality of life more pleasant, more enjoyable,

01:48:08.738 --> 01:48:16.592
[SPEAKER_72]: And so when I got to the legislature, I made it a point to bring my experience.

01:48:16.792 --> 01:48:22.122
[SPEAKER_72]: The first hearings on HIV and AIDS, I remember holding them at Plumbers Park.

01:48:22.663 --> 01:48:29.515
[SPEAKER_72]: From there came the legislation that I authored dealing with the

01:48:29.495 --> 01:48:32.284
[SPEAKER_72]: issues of standards for hospice care.

01:48:33.227 --> 01:48:38.965
[SPEAKER_72]: And of the 250 bills that were signed by three different governors,

01:48:39.940 --> 01:48:49.270
[SPEAKER_72]: The majority of them were based on the following experiences that one had, or experiences that people brought to my attention.

01:48:49.631 --> 01:48:58.060
[SPEAKER_72]: For example, I see my dear friend Monica Lozano, the daughter of the La Opinion who's seated here.

01:48:58.961 --> 01:49:03.906
[SPEAKER_72]: Her reporter reported the abuse of

01:49:04.055 --> 01:49:09.583
[SPEAKER_72]: who would send money to Mexico, and it would not get there.

01:49:11.206 --> 01:49:33.859
[SPEAKER_72]: And so I met with her, and make a long story short, today all of those money transmitters have standards, have bonding requirements, but it was the result of listening and watching and not being afraid and not being victim to circumstance and being able to deal with

01:49:34.801 --> 01:49:37.144
[SPEAKER_72]: the process, because the process works.

01:49:37.925 --> 01:49:43.512
[SPEAKER_72]: I'll end my comments today by thanking the city council.

01:49:44.874 --> 01:49:56.488
[SPEAKER_72]: I'll end my comments by saying there are issues that can, in fact, be dealt with at the local level, at the state level.

01:49:57.110 --> 01:50:12.451
[SPEAKER_72]: You represent an entity of government in the state of California that can leverage procurement so that women and minority businesses can strive.

01:50:12.772 --> 01:50:13.914
[SPEAKER_72]: Why is that important?

01:50:13.954 --> 01:50:22.105
[SPEAKER_72]: Because when they strive, those communities and that economic growth within those communities grows.

01:50:23.738 --> 01:50:29.243
[SPEAKER_72]: You have a pension fund, I would request, make sure they're not sending money to the

01:50:31.045 --> 01:50:34.428
[SPEAKER_72]: equity managers who are funding the detention facilities.

01:50:34.989 --> 01:50:44.377
[SPEAKER_72]: Make sure that the businesses in Los Angeles are not allowing for surveillance without proper authorization of our people.

01:50:45.098 --> 01:50:46.479
[SPEAKER_72]: They're popping up everywhere.

01:50:47.020 --> 01:50:57.169
[SPEAKER_72]: And so I want to just say to all of you, Mr. President, to the members of the council, you have the power to make a difference.

01:50:58.190 --> 01:51:00.512
[SPEAKER_72]: Don't be afraid to exercise it.

01:51:00.745 --> 01:51:03.768
[SPEAKER_72]: Utilize it for the betterment of people.

01:51:04.509 --> 01:51:06.691
[SPEAKER_72]: Don't make it an agenda about you.

01:51:07.391 --> 01:51:10.154
[SPEAKER_72]: Make it agenda about community.

01:51:10.855 --> 01:51:18.602
[SPEAKER_72]: And with that, I want to give special acknowledgment to the councilwoman.

01:51:18.702 --> 01:51:27.191
[SPEAKER_72]: But I want to have my family who is here, my nieces, my great-grandnieces, my cousins.

01:51:27.411 --> 01:51:30.634
[SPEAKER_72]: Please stand.

01:51:39.743 --> 01:51:47.093
[SPEAKER_72]: This is, when I ran for office, it was like I had a team.

01:51:47.533 --> 01:51:51.218
[SPEAKER_72]: And so to my family that are here, thank you so much for being here.

01:51:51.258 --> 01:51:55.383
[SPEAKER_72]: To my brother John, my parents who are up in heaven, I appreciate you.

01:51:55.403 --> 01:51:56.505
[SPEAKER_72]: I love you.

01:51:56.545 --> 01:51:57.466
[SPEAKER_72]: We miss you.

01:51:57.526 --> 01:51:58.748
[SPEAKER_72]: You're always in our hearts.

01:51:59.389 --> 01:52:01.852
[SPEAKER_72]: Again, Councilwoman, mil gracias.

01:52:02.152 --> 01:52:04.535
[SPEAKER_72]: You have no idea.

01:52:04.595 --> 01:52:08.080
[SPEAKER_72]: No idea.

01:52:15.299 --> 01:52:20.949
[SPEAKER_36]: We have to know the shoulders we're standing on.

01:52:20.969 --> 01:52:21.169
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you.

01:52:21.189 --> 01:52:22.952
[SPEAKER_36]: We have to know the shoulders that we're standing on.

01:52:23.012 --> 01:52:24.455
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you, Senator.

01:52:24.475 --> 01:52:31.547
[SPEAKER_36]: I now want to offer my colleagues an opportunity to say a few words, because I also know that your impact has reverberated here for many years.

01:52:31.927 --> 01:52:34.251
[SPEAKER_76]: Thank you so much, Council Member Hernandez.

01:52:34.271 --> 01:52:36.856
[SPEAKER_76]: And congratulations, Senator Polanco.

01:52:36.876 --> 01:52:38.558
[SPEAKER_76]: It's a long list, so I'm going to keep it short.

01:52:38.919 --> 01:52:40.682
[SPEAKER_76]: Council Member Jurado, to start.

01:52:41.658 --> 01:52:42.840
[SPEAKER_90]: Thank you, Council President.

01:52:42.880 --> 01:52:44.383
[SPEAKER_90]: Thank you, Council Member Hernandez.

01:52:44.463 --> 01:52:46.788
[SPEAKER_90]: And congratulations, Senator Polanco.

01:52:46.848 --> 01:52:49.553
[SPEAKER_90]: Your legacy has built our city.

01:52:49.573 --> 01:52:50.876
[SPEAKER_90]: It has built our state.

01:52:51.297 --> 01:52:54.763
[SPEAKER_90]: It has built my neighborhoods in CD14.

01:52:54.864 --> 01:53:01.677
