01:58:12.631 --> 01:58:18.757
[SPEAKER_59]: But again, it's just a reminder that the exposure comes early, the work comes early, and it just continues.

01:58:19.178 --> 01:58:26.746
[SPEAKER_59]: So it's very refreshing to see the giants who started the work that inspired me and that I like to think I'm continuing to move forward.

01:58:27.206 --> 01:58:30.670
[SPEAKER_59]: Thank you, Mr. Polanco, because this is your day.

01:58:34.970 --> 01:58:36.432
[SPEAKER_76]: Council Member Soto-Martinez.

01:58:37.854 --> 01:58:39.496
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you so much, Council President.

01:58:39.536 --> 01:58:46.805
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you so much, Council Member Hernandez, for putting this together, Senator Escutia, mi jefa, Marielena Durazo, Congressman Cardenas, and Senator Aralarcon.

01:58:47.405 --> 01:58:55.195
[SPEAKER_06]: You know, I love reading about history, American history, Latino history, Chicano history, the black civil rights history.

01:58:55.996 --> 01:59:01.062
[SPEAKER_06]: And you all just gave me an incredible history lesson of so much work being done in Southern California.

01:59:01.042 --> 01:59:05.666
[SPEAKER_06]: But it really crystallized when you started speaking, Senator.

01:59:07.668 --> 01:59:13.533
[SPEAKER_06]: You talked about the Great Society and the funding that came from the federal government to grassroots organizing.

01:59:13.593 --> 01:59:17.596
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't think a lot of people understand how incredible that was at the time.

01:59:18.437 --> 01:59:26.144
[SPEAKER_06]: The time that you grow up in, in the 60s, activism, you're seeing the federal government move, creating these really incredible policies.

01:59:27.025 --> 01:59:31.048
[SPEAKER_06]: I felt like when you told that story, I understood the vision that was

01:59:31.028 --> 01:59:40.465
[SPEAKER_06]: the seed that was put in your brain at that time and how all that work of the folks you're pushing, what you're striving for, you need to write a book.

01:59:40.613 --> 01:59:43.276
[SPEAKER_06]: Like, seriously, you need to write a book.

01:59:43.336 --> 01:59:43.616
[SPEAKER_06]: Second.

01:59:44.878 --> 01:59:57.572
[SPEAKER_06]: Because, you know, the difference, I would say, as a historian of this, you know, an economist of the civil rights movement, there's less aversion to folks moving from protest to politics now.

01:59:57.953 --> 02:00:00.115
[SPEAKER_06]: I think there's a hunger for that among the youth.

02:00:00.756 --> 02:00:06.823
[SPEAKER_06]: And I think Latinos don't have someone that we can look towards and say, you know what, I want to be like him.

02:00:06.803 --> 02:00:13.711
[SPEAKER_06]: You know, we talk about MLK and Ella Baker and all these amazing folks, but you have to cement your history in the city.

02:00:13.751 --> 02:00:15.253
[SPEAKER_06]: And so please write a book.

02:00:15.574 --> 02:00:19.418
[SPEAKER_06]: I want to read all the things that influenced you as a child, as a teenager, and growing up.

02:00:19.799 --> 02:00:24.645
[SPEAKER_06]: And even to this day, as you see your family and all the folks that you helped uplift.

02:00:24.665 --> 02:00:29.170
[SPEAKER_06]: And I hope to be at that book signing when you do have that book.

02:00:29.190 --> 02:00:29.831
[SPEAKER_06]: Please write a book.

02:00:30.592 --> 02:00:31.153
[SPEAKER_06]: Muchas gracias.

02:00:31.653 --> 02:00:32.094
[SPEAKER_76]: Thank you.

02:00:34.497 --> 02:00:36.439
[SPEAKER_76]: And Council Member Rodriguez to close.

02:00:37.837 --> 02:00:38.358
[SPEAKER_65]: Thank you.

02:00:38.418 --> 02:00:42.225
[SPEAKER_65]: Well, first of all, I'm not going to ask for an invitation because I will be at the square.

02:00:43.548 --> 02:00:47.094
[SPEAKER_65]: And first of all, I want to take a moment.

02:00:47.214 --> 02:00:49.719
[SPEAKER_65]: When I looked across the chamber, I see Richard Zaldivar.

02:00:50.220 --> 02:00:54.748
[SPEAKER_65]: Can all the Richard Polanco fan club please rise and be acknowledged?

02:00:55.289 --> 02:00:57.794
[SPEAKER_65]: The family, get up, get up.

02:00:58.034 --> 02:01:01.701
[SPEAKER_65]: I want everybody that's here for Richard to stand up and be recognized.

02:01:10.996 --> 02:01:19.668
[SPEAKER_65]: Because it's not just all of the incredible leaders that are here today, Marta, Maria Elena, Tony, Richard, Dean.

02:01:20.609 --> 02:01:24.735
[SPEAKER_65]: You know, I didn't have to learn this history because I watched it live.

02:01:25.175 --> 02:01:25.957
[SPEAKER_65]: I got to live it.

02:01:26.878 --> 02:01:35.029
[SPEAKER_65]: Growing up, starting my career in the Northeast, watching your legacy unfold.

02:01:35.397 --> 02:01:40.805
[SPEAKER_65]: watching you identify incredible female leaders and empower them.

02:01:42.027 --> 02:01:58.812
[SPEAKER_65]: At a time that even when I was eager to step into that role and was being told by others that didn't have the strength that you had to tell me to wait my turn, I was never about to ask for permission, never have been, never will be.

02:02:00.896 --> 02:02:02.518
[SPEAKER_65]: You were the example.

02:02:04.439 --> 02:02:08.766
[SPEAKER_65]: that machismo could be shelved for the advancement of our community.

02:02:10.349 --> 02:02:15.497
[SPEAKER_65]: You did all of this incredible work, and it wasn't just reverberated here and throughout Los Angeles.

02:02:15.598 --> 02:02:17.100
[SPEAKER_65]: It's throughout the state of California.

02:02:17.180 --> 02:02:20.065
[SPEAKER_65]: You were, in fact, the winds of change.

02:02:20.085 --> 02:02:27.898
[SPEAKER_65]: I am incredibly grateful to the friendship and the mentorship that you have been in my life, to the examples

02:02:28.385 --> 02:02:36.356
[SPEAKER_65]: to activists everywhere that think merely taking an elected seat is sufficient in leading change.

02:02:37.317 --> 02:02:40.421
[SPEAKER_65]: We aren't here to just throw stones from the outside.

02:02:41.022 --> 02:02:43.706
[SPEAKER_65]: We're here to be effective leaders on the inside.

02:02:47.151 --> 02:02:52.118
[SPEAKER_65]: It's amazing to me how many people forget that part about learning how to functionally do the work.

02:02:52.398 --> 02:02:55.422
[SPEAKER_65]: Your understanding of the rules runs deeper than your dimples.

02:03:01.477 --> 02:03:03.219
[SPEAKER_65]: And that is what's made you effective.

02:03:05.062 --> 02:03:11.390
[SPEAKER_65]: Understanding how to shift power and lead change isn't by noise alone.

02:03:12.051 --> 02:03:19.300
[SPEAKER_65]: It's by understanding the rules, understanding the structure of power, and understanding how to lead change.

02:03:19.320 --> 02:03:26.269
[SPEAKER_65]: And that's, my friend, is what's made you an incredible elected leader that has made all of this change throughout our state.

02:03:31.177 --> 02:03:41.408
[SPEAKER_65]: So congratulations on this well-deserved recognition on the future square that will be adjacent to what was formerly Laurie's.

02:03:41.488 --> 02:03:44.391
[SPEAKER_65]: I remember when it was Laurie's at the River Center.

02:03:45.272 --> 02:03:52.419
[SPEAKER_65]: And all the other things, you know, from the state park, I know you and I talked about it, the work that you did on the state park.

02:03:52.460 --> 02:03:55.783
[SPEAKER_65]: There are so many legacy projects that you have.

02:03:56.185 --> 02:04:02.975
[SPEAKER_65]: that are deserving to have your name emblazoned on it because you were, in fact, the leader that led that change.

02:04:03.796 --> 02:04:08.262
[SPEAKER_65]: But thank you for continuing to be the example and to be alongside all of these individuals.

02:04:08.282 --> 02:04:09.524
[SPEAKER_65]: They're all here for you, Richard.

02:04:09.744 --> 02:04:10.585
[SPEAKER_65]: We're all here for you.

02:04:11.426 --> 02:04:23.323
[SPEAKER_65]: Because you actually taught us how to be better at not just being the representation for our community, but how to lead the change that our community needed.

02:04:24.552 --> 02:04:28.038
[SPEAKER_65]: And you did it as recently as redistricting here in Los Angeles.

02:04:29.020 --> 02:04:43.607
[SPEAKER_65]: And while so many people want to have revisionist history about the importance of what that role was, you actually managed to ensure that our community had a very strong and unapologetic voice.

02:04:44.617 --> 02:04:48.485
[SPEAKER_65]: And I hope we continue together to be part of that voice for change.

02:04:49.107 --> 02:04:49.788
[SPEAKER_65]: I'm really proud.

02:04:49.888 --> 02:04:50.690
[SPEAKER_65]: And I want to thank you.

02:04:50.710 --> 02:04:51.772
[SPEAKER_65]: A lot of people don't know.

02:04:52.734 --> 02:05:05.241
[SPEAKER_65]: You and Marta convening everybody with LIDER to bring all the elected officials and those concerned with what's happening in this country together last year.

02:05:06.942 --> 02:05:08.745
[SPEAKER_65]: You have not retired.

02:05:09.286 --> 02:05:10.448
[SPEAKER_65]: You have not slowed down.

02:05:10.908 --> 02:05:14.514
[SPEAKER_65]: You've continued to be that strong voice for our community.

02:05:14.975 --> 02:05:16.076
[SPEAKER_65]: And Libby, thank you.

02:05:16.858 --> 02:05:18.741
[SPEAKER_65]: Because I know that's a huge sacrifice.

02:05:19.682 --> 02:05:26.693
[SPEAKER_65]: And I know how much your family has sacrificed for everything that you have done to dedicate your life to public service.

02:05:27.234 --> 02:05:34.806
[SPEAKER_65]: I'm grateful that I continue to be a student and a student of all of your work and your lessons and your example.

02:05:34.786 --> 02:05:38.351
[SPEAKER_65]: But thank you for personally being a mentor and a dear friend to me.

02:05:38.832 --> 02:05:53.894
[SPEAKER_65]: I am incredibly grateful to you and look forward to the continued leadership that you offer for our community, but not just the Latino community, for every working class community of color in the state of California.

02:05:54.214 --> 02:05:55.596
[SPEAKER_65]: You, my friend,

02:05:55.728 --> 02:05:58.151
[SPEAKER_65]: have created that legacy in history for everyone.

02:05:58.311 --> 02:06:01.354
[SPEAKER_65]: And you deserve a debt of gratitude to them.

02:06:01.374 --> 02:06:03.697
[SPEAKER_65]: So congratulations on this well-deserved honor.

02:06:04.317 --> 02:06:06.079
[SPEAKER_65]: I know this is just the start of more to come.

02:06:06.480 --> 02:06:14.108
[SPEAKER_65]: And since Heather accidentally mentioned a street, I think we should maybe consider that in front of Laurie's or in front of the River Center.

02:06:14.428 --> 02:06:22.377
[SPEAKER_65]: We need to actually, it's been an intentional activation of mine to make sure that the streets of this city

02:06:22.357 --> 02:06:34.999
[SPEAKER_65]: as we have a president that continues to try and erase our stories, that we continue to emblazon and document this living history throughout the streets of Los Angeles.

02:06:35.339 --> 02:06:41.069
[SPEAKER_65]: And I'm just glad that right now you are among those that are getting recognized for all of your incredible work.

02:06:41.089 --> 02:06:42.171
[SPEAKER_65]: Congratulations.

02:06:44.547 --> 02:06:48.933
[SPEAKER_76]: Thank you so much, Council Member Rodriguez and our colleagues.

02:06:49.113 --> 02:06:51.016
[SPEAKER_76]: All of the words are deeply felt.

02:06:51.496 --> 02:06:56.603
[SPEAKER_76]: Senator Polanco, on behalf of this council, we are very grateful to you.

02:06:56.663 --> 02:06:59.668
[SPEAKER_76]: On behalf of this city, we have tremendous gratitude.

02:06:59.848 --> 02:07:09.861
[SPEAKER_76]: I'm just struck hearing your stories this morning and thinking just a week ago, we were recognizing Reverend Jesse Jackson who had passed away.

02:07:10.863 --> 02:07:13.947
[SPEAKER_76]: And we talked about how in 84 when he ran,

02:07:14.804 --> 02:07:17.928
[SPEAKER_76]: He kicked open the door and showed people we could win.

02:07:17.968 --> 02:07:28.160
[SPEAKER_76]: And you were one of the first people to step up and run, and run without an invitation from the ruling class.

02:07:29.182 --> 02:07:33.587
[SPEAKER_76]: And you kicked in a door, and once you kick down the door, the door doesn't ever come back.

02:07:34.328 --> 02:07:36.731
[SPEAKER_76]: And so we're all very grateful for that.

02:07:36.811 --> 02:07:40.035
[SPEAKER_76]: And all of us around this horseshoe

02:07:41.146 --> 02:07:44.332
[SPEAKER_76]: We are at our best when we build on your work and build on your example.

02:07:44.392 --> 02:07:48.118
[SPEAKER_76]: So thank you so much for everything that you have done and everything that you will do.

02:07:49.921 --> 02:07:51.584
[SPEAKER_76]: Council Member Hernandez.

02:07:52.145 --> 02:07:53.187
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you, Council President.

02:07:54.729 --> 02:07:56.312
[SPEAKER_36]: Senator, if you could please join me up here.

02:07:57.033 --> 02:07:59.057
[SPEAKER_36]: A happy belated 75th birthday.

02:07:59.718 --> 02:08:02.563
[SPEAKER_36]: The city is better because of you and you deserve your flowers.

02:08:03.421 --> 02:08:08.988
[SPEAKER_36]: Now, therefore, I just want to share a little bit of love and gratitude from the city of Los Angeles.

02:08:09.308 --> 02:08:28.732
[SPEAKER_36]: And I want to express our profound gratitude to you, to Senator Richard Polanco for his distinguished legislative career, his transformative contributions to public policy, and his enduring service to the residents of the city of LA and the state of California, and many wishes of continued success into all your future endeavors.

02:08:28.752 --> 02:08:32.517
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you for letting us recognize you and for being here today with us.

02:08:37.137 --> 02:08:39.483
[SPEAKER_36]: And then we'll take more pictures in the back.

02:08:40.004 --> 02:08:40.907
[SPEAKER_36]: Come on in, come on in.

02:08:46.140 --> 02:08:51.012
[SPEAKER_36]: We're going to take more pictures in the back too.

02:09:11.427 --> 02:09:12.128
[SPEAKER_76]: Thank you so much.

02:09:12.168 --> 02:09:13.951
[SPEAKER_76]: Another big round of applause, everybody.

02:09:15.994 --> 02:09:17.416
[SPEAKER_76]: Celebrate this giant.

02:09:22.163 --> 02:09:38.869
[SPEAKER_76]: Try to give them a second to get to the back for photos as Councilmember Jurado from the First District is coming forward for our next presentation.

02:09:54.425 --> 02:10:00.775
[SPEAKER_61]: Okay, great.

02:10:01.236 --> 02:10:11.472
[SPEAKER_79]: Hold on.

02:10:12.363 --> 02:10:38.623
[SPEAKER_08]: You're a talent.

02:10:44.138 --> 02:10:46.981
[SPEAKER_85]: You're going to help dad get his award.

02:10:47.021 --> 02:10:48.102
[SPEAKER_94]: That's so nice.

02:10:48.843 --> 02:10:49.323
[SPEAKER_85]: It is.

02:10:49.444 --> 02:10:49.944
[SPEAKER_85]: Fancy.

02:10:50.685 --> 02:10:52.166
[SPEAKER_76]: You're good, you're good, you're good.

02:10:53.087 --> 02:10:53.968
[SPEAKER_76]: Hey, how are you?

02:10:54.609 --> 02:10:56.371
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

02:10:56.391 --> 02:10:57.392
[SPEAKER_17]: OK, perfect.

02:10:57.512 --> 02:10:58.273
[SPEAKER_17]: Nice.

02:10:59.374 --> 02:11:02.257
[SPEAKER_17]: Very, very nice.

02:11:02.597 --> 02:11:10.646
[SPEAKER_81]: Nice to see you.

02:11:11.126 --> 02:11:11.867
Wow.

02:11:15.526 --> 02:11:16.254
[SPEAKER_90]: Good morning.

02:11:16.315 --> 02:11:18.600
[SPEAKER_90]: It's OK.

02:11:23.356 --> 02:11:26.059
[SPEAKER_90]: Today was a great day to come to council.

02:11:26.079 --> 02:11:26.400
[SPEAKER_18]: It was.

02:11:26.420 --> 02:11:27.020
[SPEAKER_18]: Mega learning.

02:11:27.341 --> 02:11:28.502
[SPEAKER_91]: Irish dance.

02:11:28.702 --> 02:11:30.324
[SPEAKER_91]: I wore my Irish colors.

02:11:30.464 --> 02:11:31.125
[SPEAKER_91]: Oh yeah.

02:11:31.225 --> 02:11:33.087
[SPEAKER_91]: I accidentally wore green.

02:11:33.147 --> 02:11:33.508
[SPEAKER_91]: Incidentally.

02:11:33.668 --> 02:11:34.689
[SPEAKER_91]: Incidentally.

02:11:34.709 --> 02:11:36.371
[SPEAKER_91]: I'm not smart Irish, and you wouldn't do that.

02:11:36.391 --> 02:11:37.993
[SPEAKER_91]: Me too, and I didn't do that.

02:11:38.053 --> 02:11:38.353
[SPEAKER_45]: Close.

02:11:39.435 --> 02:11:40.296
[SPEAKER_91]: It's not that bad.

02:11:40.316 --> 02:11:41.257
[SPEAKER_91]: It's not that bad.

02:11:41.277 --> 02:11:41.757
[SPEAKER_91]: I told you.

02:11:41.777 --> 02:11:43.159
[SPEAKER_91]: It's not that bad.

02:11:43.519 --> 02:11:44.240
[SPEAKER_45]: But yes, it's so cool.

02:11:44.260 --> 02:11:45.462
[SPEAKER_91]: Oh my gosh, how exciting.

02:11:45.702 --> 02:11:47.284
[SPEAKER_91]: Hi, nice to see you again.

02:11:47.344 --> 02:11:48.706
[SPEAKER_91]: Nice to see you.

02:11:49.847 --> 02:11:51.569
[SPEAKER_18]: Andres, can you say hi to our council member?

02:11:51.609 --> 02:11:52.570
[SPEAKER_91]: Hey.

02:11:52.550 --> 02:12:21.628
[SPEAKER_90]: If we could get the chatter down to a low level.

02:12:22.857 --> 02:12:31.770
[SPEAKER_76]: And we will give the floor to our colleagues, Council Members Jurado and Soto-Martinez.

02:12:31.790 --> 02:12:33.071
[SPEAKER_90]: Good morning, everyone.

02:12:33.111 --> 02:12:42.104
[SPEAKER_90]: It's an honor to recognize the service of Reverend Zachary Hoover, whose leadership, faith, and advocacy have supported our communities.

02:12:42.545 --> 02:12:51.177
[SPEAKER_90]: A man who has turned faith into action over and over again for a decade of service as Executive Director of LA Voice.

02:12:55.139 --> 02:13:03.672
[SPEAKER_90]: I know many of us here have worked with LA Voice where Reverend Zachary has helped bring together a remarkable coalition of congregations across LA County.

02:13:04.273 --> 02:13:11.764
[SPEAKER_90]: At his core, he is someone who believes deeply in people and in their dignity and their power when they come together.

02:13:11.744 --> 02:13:15.708
[SPEAKER_90]: During his time at LA Voice, that work has taken many forms.

02:13:16.209 --> 02:13:30.384
[SPEAKER_90]: Through organizing campaigns, he has expanded access to groceries in neighborhoods, long considered food deserts, and pushed major financial institutions to reinvest in their communities that too often been overlooked.

02:13:30.404 --> 02:13:40.975
[SPEAKER_90]: He has helped increase voter participation in communities of color, remove barriers to employment for people returning home after incarceration, and built bridges between communities.

02:13:41.613 --> 02:13:46.181
[SPEAKER_90]: Reverend Zachary has also played a key role in efforts to expand affordable housing.

02:13:46.701 --> 02:14:03.790
[SPEAKER_90]: Through initiatives like the Innovative Faith and Housing Program, he helped make it easier for faith institutions to utilize their land to build affordable housing, bringing together faith-based communities and housing advocates to address one of the most urgent challenges here in Los Angeles.

02:14:03.770 --> 02:14:08.959
[SPEAKER_90]: And what stands out about Reverend Zachary is not just what he does, but it's how he does it.

02:14:09.561 --> 02:14:10.703
[SPEAKER_90]: He listens first.

02:14:11.164 --> 02:14:12.566
[SPEAKER_90]: He treats people with respect.

02:14:13.327 --> 02:14:15.191
[SPEAKER_90]: He makes space for others to lead.

02:14:15.892 --> 02:14:27.313
[SPEAKER_90]: Whether he's working with clergy, training organizers across the country, or collaborating with community leaders, he brings a humility and sincerity that people immediately feel.

02:14:27.293 --> 02:14:29.936
[SPEAKER_90]: He reminds us that real change doesn't happen overnight.

02:14:29.976 --> 02:14:33.781
[SPEAKER_90]: It happens through relationships, perseverance, and faith.

02:14:33.841 --> 02:14:42.312
[SPEAKER_90]: And that kind of faith that believes communities can overcome division and build something together.

02:14:43.574 --> 02:14:45.536
[SPEAKER_90]: So thank you, Zachary, Reverend Zachary.

02:14:45.577 --> 02:14:49.842
[SPEAKER_90]: And now I'd like to turn it over to my colleague council member Soto Martinez.

02:14:53.213 --> 02:14:55.035
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you so much, Councilman Jurado.

02:14:55.556 --> 02:15:02.465
[SPEAKER_06]: It's great to be here to honor an incredible leader that I've had the privilege of working with many times during my own career.

02:15:03.206 --> 02:15:14.801
[SPEAKER_06]: Reverend Hoover has been a powerful voice for the poor and working people, the working class in the city of Los Angeles, for more than a decade in LA Voice, but if you add his entire career, almost two decades.

02:15:15.241 --> 02:15:19.727
[SPEAKER_06]: First as an organizer, eventually as an executive director of LA Voice.

02:15:19.707 --> 02:15:33.466
[SPEAKER_06]: Through their organizing work, I've seen firsthand how LA Voice has protected immigrants, uplifted renters, and brought more opportunities to communities that have been ignored by this city for decades.

02:15:33.486 --> 02:15:42.940
[SPEAKER_06]: Reverend Hoover is a true man of faith, one that believes our spirituality needs to be at the core of our activism and our organizing and our protests.

02:15:44.021 --> 02:15:45.343
[SPEAKER_06]: When I first met

02:15:46.184 --> 02:15:50.210
[SPEAKER_06]: the Reverend, we was like an immediate connection.

02:15:50.310 --> 02:15:54.938
[SPEAKER_06]: We started talking about how spirituality needs to be at the front and center of the work that we do.

02:15:55.278 --> 02:16:07.197
[SPEAKER_06]: We talked about Reverend Lawson and nonviolent direct action and how when you fight, it's not about just trying to defeat your opponent, but trying to win over your opponent so they can see your point of view.

02:16:07.177 --> 02:16:12.382
[SPEAKER_06]: He places the needs of others first, and he's been an amazing ally in fighting for justice in this city.

02:16:13.003 --> 02:16:17.547
[SPEAKER_06]: No matter where he goes next, I'm certain we'll continue to see him out there fighting the good fight.

02:16:18.328 --> 02:16:24.834
[SPEAKER_06]: So Reverend Hoover, thank you for all the work that you do, for making us believe in progress, and best of luck to you in your next chapter.

02:16:29.018 --> 02:16:33.943
[SPEAKER_90]: And now it's my distinct honor to welcome Reverend Zachary Hoover to share a few words.

02:16:41.281 --> 02:16:48.571
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you both so much, Councilmember Soto-Martinez, and my councilmember, whom I share a street with, Councilmember Jurado.

02:16:48.591 --> 02:16:49.513
[SPEAKER_18]: It's really great to be here.

02:16:49.533 --> 02:16:54.600
[SPEAKER_18]: I remember when I started at LA Voice as an organizer, sometimes we had trouble even getting meetings in this building.

02:16:55.181 --> 02:17:00.649
[SPEAKER_18]: And now here we are, all together with staff and friends and people that we've done work with over the years.

02:17:01.991 --> 02:17:06.377
[SPEAKER_18]: When your staff person, Isabella, told us that it might be at least 90 minutes before it would be our turn,

02:17:06.357 --> 02:17:09.236
[SPEAKER_18]: I told my wife and son, and she said, 90 minutes.

02:17:09.377 --> 02:17:11.309
[SPEAKER_18]: And I said, babe, you're Latina, and I'm Irish.

02:17:11.370 --> 02:17:12.638
[SPEAKER_18]: It's going to be 90 minutes.

02:17:14.339 --> 02:17:20.106
[SPEAKER_18]: So I just want to thank the two of you for creating this opportunity.

02:17:21.849 --> 02:17:35.066
[SPEAKER_18]: For me, it's about the work that LA Voice has been able to do over the years with partners in this room and with grassroots leaders all across LA County, our board members, our staff, and just regular folks from communities in Los Angeles.

02:17:35.526 --> 02:17:36.247
[SPEAKER_18]: I have fond memories.

02:17:36.287 --> 02:17:39.672
[SPEAKER_18]: It was cool to see Mr. Alarcón here.

02:17:39.752 --> 02:17:43.637
