02:44:01.450 --> 02:44:10.140
[SPEAKER_36]: It's a pleasure to lead today's presentation to recognize United Teachers Los Angeles, UTLA, and SEIU Local 99.

02:44:10.424 --> 02:44:14.092
[SPEAKER_36]: Four, their relentless work on the front lines of our public schools.

02:44:14.773 --> 02:44:17.980
[SPEAKER_36]: Councilmember Soto-Martinez and I are proud to welcome you to the People's House.

02:44:18.441 --> 02:44:23.492
[SPEAKER_36]: By bringing your fight here, you're showing the city of Los Angeles that we stand shoulder to shoulder with you.

02:44:24.033 --> 02:44:28.663
[SPEAKER_36]: And when you sit at the bargaining table with LAUSD, you are not alone because the people are with you.

02:44:29.224 --> 02:44:30.407
[SPEAKER_36]: We are with you.

02:44:30.387 --> 02:44:31.851
[SPEAKER_36]: We have a powerhouse lineup today.

02:44:32.372 --> 02:44:33.114
[SPEAKER_36]: We should be lucky.

02:44:34.077 --> 02:44:40.093
[SPEAKER_36]: Normally, we get a lot of great people that come in, but one day to have this many number of great people is pretty exciting.

02:44:41.035 --> 02:44:45.527
[SPEAKER_36]: We have Yvonne Wheeler, president of the LA Fed, joining us, who's with us here today.

02:44:45.507 --> 02:44:48.912
[SPEAKER_36]: Julie Van Winkle, UTLA AFT Vice President.

02:44:49.292 --> 02:44:51.796
[SPEAKER_36]: Max Arias, Executive Director of SEIU99.

02:44:52.957 --> 02:44:55.461
[SPEAKER_36]: Titans in the world of labor.

02:44:56.142 --> 02:44:59.386
[SPEAKER_36]: In a few moments, they will lay out the cold, hard facts.

02:44:59.406 --> 02:45:04.213
[SPEAKER_36]: They will speak about the struggles of working class families and the very real struggle for a fair contract.

02:45:04.714 --> 02:45:08.519
[SPEAKER_36]: But before we move on, I think it's only right that I restate the obvious.

02:45:09.060 --> 02:45:12.865
[SPEAKER_36]: The history of public education is a history of struggle.

02:45:12.845 --> 02:45:17.711
[SPEAKER_36]: It's as if some people forgot that the right to public education was fought and won.

02:45:18.352 --> 02:45:19.994
[SPEAKER_36]: Today, that fight continues.

02:45:20.355 --> 02:45:32.050
[SPEAKER_36]: And when we talk about fighting for our public schools, and when we talk about throwing down for our youth, we must understand that it also means fighting for the people who educate them, who feed them, and care for them, our young people every single day.

02:45:32.591 --> 02:45:35.635
[SPEAKER_36]: Throwing down for the future of Los Angeles means throwing down for educators.

02:45:36.016 --> 02:45:37.738
[SPEAKER_36]: Isn't that right, UTLA?

02:45:37.718 --> 02:45:42.307
[SPEAKER_36]: Throwing down means good working conditions, good benefits.

02:45:42.647 --> 02:45:43.909
[SPEAKER_36]: Isn't that right, SEIU99?

02:45:45.993 --> 02:45:46.474
[SPEAKER_36]: That's right.

02:45:46.835 --> 02:45:51.463
[SPEAKER_36]: We cannot expect our students to thrive if the workers supporting them are struggling to survive.

02:45:51.984 --> 02:46:01.482
[SPEAKER_36]: Educators are fighting to build schools where educators are proud to work, where students are fully supported, and where every single family is proud to send their children.

02:46:01.462 --> 02:46:09.399
[SPEAKER_36]: And so I urge LAUSD to do the right thing by the people, and I call on Angelenos to stand with educators always.

02:46:10.040 --> 02:46:14.830
[SPEAKER_36]: Now, please make some noise for our next speaker, my colleague, Council Member Hugo Soto-Martinez.

02:46:17.881 --> 02:46:24.657
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you so much, Councilwoman Hernandez, and thank you for introducing and bringing forth so many amazing, powerful folks from the labor movement.

02:46:25.199 --> 02:46:31.654
[SPEAKER_06]: It's always good to have the House of Labor here, but it wouldn't be the House of Labor if we didn't have a union clap, so how do we get that started, huh?

02:46:40.358 --> 02:46:41.840
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you so much.

02:46:42.520 --> 02:46:50.269
[SPEAKER_06]: We are here today to recognize two incredible unions that have been fighting for students, families, and the future generations of Angelenos.

02:46:51.110 --> 02:46:57.356
[SPEAKER_06]: Nelson Mandela said it best, education is the most powerful weapon which you can use to change the world.

02:46:57.897 --> 02:47:04.324
[SPEAKER_06]: And the workers of SAU 99 and UTLA dedicate their lives to that very simple idea.

02:47:04.304 --> 02:47:19.799
[SPEAKER_06]: And as a student of nonviolent direct action, we know that young people and educators have always been at the core of social justice movements, from apartheid in South Africa with Steve Biko, to colonial India, to the civil right movement here at home with SNCC.

02:47:20.220 --> 02:47:23.743
[SPEAKER_06]: It is young people and educators that have been a part at the tip of the spear.

02:47:24.464 --> 02:47:32.472
[SPEAKER_06]: We saw that leadership firsthand when the federal government invaded our communities last summer, and as they continue to rip our families apart to this day.

02:47:32.452 --> 02:47:41.483
[SPEAKER_06]: Our educators organized, mobilized, and built a network within weeks to ensure that safe passage was available to our children and our families.

02:47:42.003 --> 02:47:48.950
[SPEAKER_06]: These heroes stepped up for our communities, and now they need our support as they fight for their own dignity and their own futures.

02:47:49.471 --> 02:47:52.354
[SPEAKER_06]: But they're not asking for us to do it for them.

02:47:52.394 --> 02:47:55.237
[SPEAKER_06]: They're asking us to be there with them in solidarity.

02:47:55.317 --> 02:47:57.320
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's what was at the heart of the labor movement.

02:47:57.980 --> 02:48:09.833
[SPEAKER_06]: Our education workers, the teaching aides, bus drivers, support staff, and everyone who makes sure that our kids are safe and have a loving place to learn cannot afford to live in the city that they work in.

02:48:09.813 --> 02:48:13.658
[SPEAKER_06]: Too many of these workers rely on public assistance to put food on the table.

02:48:14.319 --> 02:48:17.623
[SPEAKER_06]: Too many of them have to work a second job just to make ends meet.

02:48:18.224 --> 02:48:23.791
[SPEAKER_06]: Too many of them have experienced homelessness even as they hold jobs with the school board with LAUSD.

02:48:24.612 --> 02:48:28.717
[SPEAKER_06]: That is not a reality that we should be willing to accept any single day.

02:48:28.757 --> 02:48:31.180
[SPEAKER_06]: Not now, not yesterday, not in the future.

02:48:33.117 --> 02:48:40.086
[SPEAKER_06]: These are the people caring for our children, and they deserve fair wages, stable working conditions, and respect in the workplace.

02:48:40.386 --> 02:48:43.630
[SPEAKER_06]: It doesn't matter if it's a private employer or a public sector employer.

02:48:43.970 --> 02:48:46.874
[SPEAKER_06]: They deserve it regardless of who they're working for.

02:48:46.934 --> 02:48:52.060
[SPEAKER_06]: That's why we need to support them right now, just like they support our communities every single day.

02:48:52.601 --> 02:48:58.528
[SPEAKER_06]: So today, I want to celebrate our educators and encourage all of you to join them in their fight for a fair contract.

02:48:59.009 --> 02:49:00.711
[SPEAKER_06]: Because if they aren't listening now,

02:49:01.484 --> 02:49:04.290
[SPEAKER_06]: we'll make sure that they have no choice but to listen to us.

02:49:04.891 --> 02:49:08.098
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you so much.

02:49:08.820 --> 02:49:09.361
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you.

02:49:11.566 --> 02:49:18.801
[SPEAKER_36]: And now please make some noise for the icon Yvonne Wheeler, president of the LA Fed.

02:49:20.114 --> 02:49:24.426
[SPEAKER_23]: Good afternoon, Council President and distinguished members of the City Council.

02:49:24.526 --> 02:49:36.418
[SPEAKER_23]: My name is Yvonne Wheeler, and I'm the president of the Los Angeles County Federation of Labor, representing over 800,000 union members and over 300 union affiliates in Los Angeles County.

02:49:36.398 --> 02:49:46.215
[SPEAKER_23]: And I'm proud to stand here in solidarity with the workers of the United Teachers of Los Angeles, UTLA, and SEIU Local 99.

02:49:46.816 --> 02:49:52.686
[SPEAKER_23]: Public education is one of the most transformative economic mobilities in our nation's history.

02:49:53.459 --> 02:49:58.226
[SPEAKER_23]: empowering millions of people to build lives and dignity and security.

02:49:58.907 --> 02:50:00.850
[SPEAKER_23]: But none of this happens by accident.

02:50:01.592 --> 02:50:14.151
[SPEAKER_23]: It is the countless hours that educators, counselors, nurses, and social workers of UTLA spend instructing and caring for our students that make public schools places of possibility.

02:50:14.131 --> 02:50:27.728
[SPEAKER_23]: It is the hard work of the bus drivers, teacher's aides, and cafeteria workers, custodians of SEIU Local 99, who keep our students safe, fed, and cared for every single day.

02:50:28.489 --> 02:50:31.453
[SPEAKER_23]: These workers love their profession.

02:50:31.813 --> 02:50:32.975
[SPEAKER_23]: They love their students.

02:50:33.135 --> 02:50:35.938
[SPEAKER_23]: And they love their communities that they live in.

02:50:36.559 --> 02:50:43.007
[SPEAKER_23]: Yet, far too many educators and educated workers are struggling to make ends meet.

02:50:43.645 --> 02:50:52.901
[SPEAKER_23]: Too many have been forced to make impossible situations and heartbreaking sacrifices just to continue serving their students.

02:50:53.622 --> 02:50:59.713
[SPEAKER_23]: Meanwhile, LAUSD is sitting on more than $5 billion in reserve.

02:50:59.997 --> 02:51:03.662
[SPEAKER_23]: Yet workers have been left without a fair contract for years.

02:51:04.162 --> 02:51:13.855
[SPEAKER_23]: Instead of investing in the people who make the schools work, the district continues contracting out essential programs to multi-billion dollar corporations.

02:51:14.636 --> 02:51:23.727
[SPEAKER_23]: These workers are not only fighting for themselves, they are fighting for the fully staffed and fully funded public schools that anchor our communities.

02:51:24.247 --> 02:51:28.011
[SPEAKER_23]: Our public dollars should not go to corporations.

02:51:28.031 --> 02:51:30.674
[SPEAKER_23]: They should go into the classrooms to serve the students.

02:51:31.355 --> 02:51:38.002
[SPEAKER_23]: It is long past time for LAUSD to give them a fair contract.

02:51:38.042 --> 02:51:49.335
[SPEAKER_23]: And I urge this body to stand with the educators, stand with SEIU Local 99, stand with UTLA, and stand with these workers and get the contract that they fairly deserve.

02:51:49.355 --> 02:51:50.136
[SPEAKER_23]: Thank you.

02:51:54.757 --> 02:51:55.481
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you so much.

02:51:56.024 --> 02:52:01.898
[SPEAKER_36]: Now please join me in welcoming Julie Van Winkle, UTLA AFT Vice President.

02:52:04.848 --> 02:52:06.151
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Councilmembers.

02:52:06.231 --> 02:52:11.100
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Council President and the entire City Council for the opportunity to speak with you today.

02:52:11.942 --> 02:52:14.907
[SPEAKER_17]: We are the public school educators of Los Angeles.

02:52:15.188 --> 02:52:25.067
[SPEAKER_17]: UTLA represents 38,000 teachers, special educators, counselors, nurses, social workers, librarians, and more.

02:52:25.047 --> 02:52:31.889
[SPEAKER_17]: My fellow educators and I are proud to have dedicated our profession to serving students, families, and communities of Los Angeles.

02:52:32.532 --> 02:52:37.588
[SPEAKER_17]: We believe deeply in the need and value of public schools now more than ever.

02:52:38.868 --> 02:52:48.222
[SPEAKER_17]: We know that our public education is under attack, not just by the Trump administration, but by billionaire privatizers who are hell-bent on turning our students into profits.

