[SPEAKER_17]: Now we're struggling just to afford rent anywhere within the district boundaries.

02:53:29.098 --> 02:53:37.853
[SPEAKER_17]: We've received a lot of heartbreaking testimonials from our members who share that they're putting off starting families or they're not able to retire because they just don't make enough money.

02:53:38.574 --> 02:53:41.359
[SPEAKER_17]: And this is not right and it's certainly not sustainable.

02:53:42.757 --> 02:53:49.624
[SPEAKER_17]: For years, our district has prioritized contracting over meeting the needs and demands of our educators and education workers.

02:53:50.304 --> 02:54:00.494
[SPEAKER_17]: In the last few years, LA Unified has spent over $6.7 billion of public money on private contracts and private companies.

02:54:01.455 --> 02:54:03.237
[SPEAKER_17]: And many of these are in big tech.

02:54:04.038 --> 02:54:08.562
[SPEAKER_17]: And this is while failing to meet the state requirements on spending in classroom instruction.

02:54:10.280 --> 02:54:18.939
[SPEAKER_17]: The district, as Yvonne said, is currently sitting on over $5 billion in reserves and is projected to receive increased funding from the state this year.

02:54:19.781 --> 02:54:22.266
[SPEAKER_17]: There's more than enough money to strengthen our schools.

02:54:22.407 --> 02:54:24.131
[SPEAKER_17]: It's not about not having the money.

02:54:24.251 --> 02:54:26.315
[SPEAKER_17]: It's about not having the priorities.

02:54:26.375 --> 02:54:28.440
[SPEAKER_17]: And we need the district to have priority.

02:54:28.420 --> 02:54:34.066
[SPEAKER_17]: to make sure that educators are able to live in the city and that our schools have the supports right now that they deserve.

02:54:34.667 --> 02:54:40.413
[SPEAKER_17]: Our fight is about making sure that today's dollars go into our classrooms and not into the pockets of billionaires.

02:54:41.674 --> 02:54:44.497
[SPEAKER_17]: Our working conditions are our students' learning conditions.

02:54:45.098 --> 02:54:53.247
[SPEAKER_17]: Our contract demands were developed democratically by educators, parents, students, and community members, and they reflect the needs of our schools.

02:54:53.227 --> 02:55:04.992
[SPEAKER_17]: We're fighting for fair pay, smaller class sizes, more mental health supports, increased arts and PE education, more support for special education, and much, much more.

02:55:06.507 --> 02:55:16.166
[SPEAKER_17]: And I'm asking all of you on the council, everybody watching this, you can even scan the QR code there, to join us on March 18th for our rally for the fight for LA.

02:55:16.227 --> 02:55:28.431
[SPEAKER_17]: We need to show the leaders of LA Unified, some of which own six or seven houses here in California and in Florida, while our workers in the schools can't even afford to pay rent.

02:55:28.411 --> 02:55:37.321
[SPEAKER_17]: We are asking you to join us to tell them that they need to settle our contract and give our students and our communities and our educators what they deserve.

02:55:37.882 --> 02:55:38.602
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you so much.

02:55:43.628 --> 02:55:44.309
[SPEAKER_36]: Absolutely.

02:55:44.389 --> 02:55:47.793
[SPEAKER_36]: We are we're not going to let them continue to get away with that.

02:55:47.813 --> 02:55:50.556
[SPEAKER_36]: And I think that's why we're here today to show you that we are with you.

02:55:51.457 --> 02:55:57.844
[SPEAKER_36]: Now let's hear for let's hear it up for our final speaker Max Arias executive director of SEIU 99.

02:56:00.845 --> 02:56:01.987
[SPEAKER_07]: Good afternoon.

02:56:02.007 --> 02:56:05.655
[SPEAKER_07]: By now, council members appreciate the opportunity.

02:56:06.156 --> 02:56:07.198
[SPEAKER_07]: My name is Max Arias.

02:56:07.399 --> 02:56:11.607
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm executive director elected of SCAU Local 99 Education Workers United.

02:56:12.048 --> 02:56:15.816
[SPEAKER_07]: We are over 50,000 education workers strong representing childcare providers.

02:56:16.100 --> 02:56:19.866
[SPEAKER_07]: TK-12 classified employees, as well as community college classified.

02:56:21.148 --> 02:56:22.009
[SPEAKER_07]: Next, please.

02:56:22.690 --> 02:56:26.596
[SPEAKER_07]: At the LA Unified School District, we represent 30,000 workers.

02:56:26.857 --> 02:56:28.579
[SPEAKER_07]: Next slide, please.

02:56:28.719 --> 02:56:31.904
[SPEAKER_07]: And that is who we are, paraeducators, bus drivers, et cetera.

02:56:31.924 --> 02:56:34.048
[SPEAKER_07]: You can see there, over 100 classifications.

02:56:34.408 --> 02:56:36.572
[SPEAKER_07]: Without our members, the district does not wake up.

02:56:37.152 --> 02:56:38.555
[SPEAKER_07]: Children will not get to school.

02:56:38.915 --> 02:56:42.040
[SPEAKER_07]: Children will not eat nutritious meals.

02:56:42.020 --> 02:56:47.642
[SPEAKER_07]: Teachers need the support that our members give them in the classroom, especially if we continue to have these large classroom sizes.

02:56:47.743 --> 02:56:50.072
[SPEAKER_07]: We need to change that too.

02:56:51.031 --> 02:56:52.252
[SPEAKER_07]: Who we are, our demographics.

02:56:52.753 --> 02:56:54.996
[SPEAKER_07]: We are a predominantly black and brown workforce.

02:56:55.016 --> 02:56:59.221
[SPEAKER_07]: In fact, over 90% of classified workers are people of color.

02:56:59.921 --> 02:57:02.805
[SPEAKER_07]: Further, it's a majority woman workforce.

02:57:02.825 --> 02:57:09.993
[SPEAKER_07]: And just to remind, we're right now in Women's History Month, so it's important to note that we need to start doing something about it.

02:57:10.073 --> 02:57:12.296
[SPEAKER_07]: It's too late in society to have this situation.

02:57:13.137 --> 02:57:19.384
[SPEAKER_07]: And 43% of classified employees are parents of school-age children, many who attend LUSD schools.

02:57:19.752 --> 02:57:23.618
[SPEAKER_07]: However, how do we treat these women and students of the district, right?

02:57:23.698 --> 02:57:24.639
[SPEAKER_07]: You can see right there.

02:57:25.481 --> 02:57:28.425
[SPEAKER_07]: Local 99 members get paid poverty wages.

02:57:28.545 --> 02:57:29.627
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm just going to put it out there.

02:57:29.827 --> 02:57:36.958
[SPEAKER_07]: The average class of an employee makes only $35,000 a year, some as little as $29,000 a year.

02:57:37.478 --> 02:57:48.595
[SPEAKER_07]: This is way below, Salud, way below the poverty line, way below just about any poverty line, especially in the city of LA, where it takes $57,000 for an individual to be able to

02:57:48.575 --> 02:57:50.158
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, actually, that's the poverty line.

02:57:50.178 --> 02:57:51.841
[SPEAKER_07]: So that's not OK.

02:57:52.462 --> 02:57:58.753
[SPEAKER_07]: So as a result, 99% of our members cannot afford a one bedroom apartment in LA.

02:57:58.773 --> 02:57:59.834
[SPEAKER_07]: 99%.

02:57:59.855 --> 02:58:05.925
[SPEAKER_07]: 65% or 20,000 people struggle with food insecurity.

02:58:05.905 --> 02:58:07.207
[SPEAKER_07]: because they cannot afford food.

02:58:07.868 --> 02:58:10.952
[SPEAKER_07]: One in three, or 10,000 people, are on public assistance.

02:58:11.313 --> 02:58:21.447
[SPEAKER_07]: And 10% of our members, 3,000 people, have expressed housing insecurity while working for the largest district in the state, which is the second largest district in the nation.

02:58:21.647 --> 02:58:23.069
[SPEAKER_07]: This has impact on students.

02:58:23.410 --> 02:58:33.043
[SPEAKER_07]: The low staffing of custodial staff, which is staffed at only 40% of what the district needs, needs the bathrooms being closed, and not every school in the district

02:58:33.023 --> 02:58:40.468
[SPEAKER_07]: having the cleanliness it needs, it deserves, that students deserve to be able to learn in dignity.

02:58:41.613 --> 02:58:43.536
[SPEAKER_07]: What are we demanding at the end of the day?

02:58:44.317 --> 02:58:48.183
[SPEAKER_07]: We have been bargaining for the district for two years, two years at that sink in.

02:58:48.203 --> 02:58:49.645
[SPEAKER_07]: In 23, we had to strike.

02:58:50.286 --> 02:58:55.934
[SPEAKER_07]: Where 25,000 was the average wage in 23, we got it to 35,000.

02:58:55.974 --> 02:58:57.536
[SPEAKER_07]: That's still not enough.

02:58:58.037 --> 02:59:01.783
[SPEAKER_07]: And we had to strike for the same reason, disrespect and harassment.

02:59:01.803 --> 02:59:02.984
[SPEAKER_07]: For two years, we've been bargaining.

02:59:03.024 --> 02:59:04.206
[SPEAKER_07]: The district has stalled us.

02:59:04.607 --> 02:59:06.810
[SPEAKER_07]: The district has harassed our members to the point

02:59:06.790 --> 02:59:14.045
[SPEAKER_07]: We've had to file multiple and multiple ULPs, that's charges against them for not respecting workers' rights.

02:59:14.847 --> 02:59:16.891
[SPEAKER_07]: And our members took a strike vote.

02:59:16.931 --> 02:59:24.808
[SPEAKER_07]: 97% are ready to walk out because of this treatment and because they are struggling and we have had enough of this.

02:59:25.589 --> 02:59:27.313
[SPEAKER_07]: So, what are our demands?

02:59:27.665 --> 02:59:30.069
[SPEAKER_07]: Let's restore hours to provide essential student services.

02:59:30.570 --> 02:59:35.059
[SPEAKER_07]: We cannot continue to cut workers hours consistently to try to balance the budget.

02:59:35.419 --> 02:59:36.682
[SPEAKER_07]: It doesn't balance the budget.

02:59:37.083 --> 02:59:39.307
[SPEAKER_07]: You've heard of the layoffs the district is trying to implement.

02:59:39.968 --> 02:59:47.943
[SPEAKER_07]: They're trying to save 25 million dollars and it really has a horrible impact on people's lives and students in the school sites.

02:59:47.963 --> 02:59:50.247
[SPEAKER_07]: We're also demanding higher wages.

02:59:50.227 --> 02:59:50.888
[SPEAKER_07]: High wages.

02:59:51.749 --> 02:59:54.172
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't have to give any justification why.

02:59:54.472 --> 02:59:55.734
[SPEAKER_07]: They work for the school district.

02:59:55.754 --> 02:59:58.577
[SPEAKER_07]: They educate the children of LA and the students of LA.

02:59:59.198 --> 03:00:04.785
[SPEAKER_07]: So why should they be living on poverty wages in which they have to worry about what to eat?

03:00:05.246 --> 03:00:07.028
[SPEAKER_07]: No, it is completely unacceptable.

03:00:07.328 --> 03:00:10.833
[SPEAKER_07]: We are demanding that they stop outsourcing to private for-profit companies.

03:00:11.654 --> 03:00:14.277
[SPEAKER_07]: Ever since the new superintendent came in,

03:00:14.662 --> 03:00:16.845
[SPEAKER_07]: I won't say a name because right now he's in some process.

03:00:17.586 --> 03:00:22.392
[SPEAKER_07]: They've spent $650 million a year in contracting out services.

03:00:22.492 --> 03:00:26.617
[SPEAKER_07]: Before he came, it was $250 million a year, which is also obscene.

03:00:26.918 --> 03:00:30.082
[SPEAKER_07]: But $650 million a year, that is not.

03:00:30.142 --> 03:00:34.948
[SPEAKER_07]: So when they tell you they spend more than they receive, we ask them, where?

03:00:34.928 --> 03:00:39.553
[SPEAKER_07]: The last demand is, well, there's many other demands, respect and dignity in the workplace.

03:00:40.013 --> 03:00:42.636
[SPEAKER_07]: It is no coincidence that our members are in this situation.

03:00:42.656 --> 03:00:53.568
[SPEAKER_07]: It is decades of not valuing the work they do, not valuing who they are, because of who they are, black and brown woman, it is expected that they're supposed to work for miserly wages.

03:00:53.928 --> 03:00:54.950
[SPEAKER_07]: That is unacceptable.

03:00:55.070 --> 03:00:56.191
[SPEAKER_07]: We will not put up with it.

03:00:56.611 --> 03:01:02.758
[SPEAKER_07]: And we really thank you for considering the support, and we really ask for your support.

03:01:02.738 --> 03:01:07.388
[SPEAKER_07]: Unlike the city or county of Los Angeles, LAUSD is not facing state cuts.

03:01:07.909 --> 03:01:13.581
[SPEAKER_07]: In fact, California continues to make record-breaking investments in schools, with more money coming for the school year.

03:01:14.343 --> 03:01:19.313
[SPEAKER_07]: LAUSD does not have a budget problem, it has a priority problem.

03:01:19.293 --> 03:01:24.020
[SPEAKER_07]: LAU is these $5 billion, let me say again, $5,000 million.

03:01:24.040 --> 03:01:29.189
[SPEAKER_07]: Because I think we're a little, when we hear $5 billion, we don't really think about what that means.

03:01:29.930 --> 03:01:35.158
[SPEAKER_07]: Those reserves themselves are more than double the budget of LAX.

03:01:36.400 --> 03:01:42.229
[SPEAKER_07]: And $5 billion is 35% of the city's operating budget.

03:01:42.428 --> 03:01:44.531
[SPEAKER_07]: That's what much they have sitting in the bank.

03:01:45.031 --> 03:01:49.336
[SPEAKER_07]: While our school employees continue to suffer, executive pay continues to climb.

03:01:49.777 --> 03:01:54.643
[SPEAKER_07]: There are over 200 LAUSD executives who make more than the governor of California.

03:01:55.544 --> 03:01:58.227
[SPEAKER_07]: Workers are a breaking point.

03:01:58.247 --> 03:02:07.037
[SPEAKER_07]: We ask the LA City Council to stand in solidarity with the workers who support our children and keep our campuses clean, safe, and supportive.

03:02:07.057 --> 03:02:07.558
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

03:02:13.985 --> 03:02:15.347
[SPEAKER_76]: Thank you so much, members.

03:02:15.367 --> 03:02:18.172
[SPEAKER_76]: We've got a couple of members on the queue, beginning with Council Member McOsker.

03:02:20.076 --> 03:02:25.445
[SPEAKER_74]: Thank you so much, Council Members, for bringing UTLA and 99 in today.

03:02:25.505 --> 03:02:36.364
[SPEAKER_74]: And thank you so much, Council Members Hernandez and Hugo Soto-Martinez, for giving me the opportunity to second, among other members, a motion in support of your efforts.

03:02:37.137 --> 03:02:38.079
[SPEAKER_74]: in support of your efforts.

03:02:38.099 --> 03:02:45.653
[SPEAKER_74]: I'm quite confident that we will be unanimously in support of your efforts as UTLA and SEIU 99.

03:02:46.715 --> 03:02:50.302
[SPEAKER_74]: Many of you know, my wife is a retired UTLA teacher.

03:02:51.184 --> 03:02:56.935
[SPEAKER_74]: She was in adult education for about 30 years, which means they laid her off about three or four times.

03:02:57.488 --> 03:03:02.558
[SPEAKER_74]: And they cut her hours so that they could save on benefits and did all kinds of things to her.

03:03:02.879 --> 03:03:09.973
[SPEAKER_74]: And every single time, she turned to UTLA, and you had her back, every single time.

03:03:11.056 --> 03:03:16.206
[SPEAKER_74]: And I'm acutely aware of the fact that my wife, Connie McOsker, in my community,

03:03:16.777 --> 03:03:26.449
[SPEAKER_74]: even treated that way by LAUSD in her time in the classroom has had more effect on goodness in our community and uplifting folks.

03:03:26.829 --> 03:03:41.046
[SPEAKER_74]: Teaching ESL and citizenship and parenting education has had more effect in just a year of her practice that she did for 30 years than I will ever have, than I will ever have.

03:03:41.802 --> 03:03:53.679
[SPEAKER_74]: Because the work that you do in the classroom and the work you do on the campuses is so critically important to the future of our city and the future of our society.

03:03:54.299 --> 03:03:58.665
[SPEAKER_74]: You affect our world more than this horseshoe ever will.

03:03:59.987 --> 03:04:09.160
[SPEAKER_74]: And this indignity that you are facing from LAUSD is not them doing it to you.

03:04:09.629 --> 03:04:10.150
[SPEAKER_74]: It is us.

03:04:10.470 --> 03:04:11.211
[SPEAKER_74]: It is all of us.

03:04:12.032 --> 03:04:15.776
[SPEAKER_74]: This is our public system and we need to all own it.

03:04:16.237 --> 03:04:31.836
[SPEAKER_74]: We need to all own the fact that this is how we currently today in 2026 are teaching are treating teachers and professionals who keep our schools open and keep our schools safe and keep them clean and keep them well equipped.

03:04:32.677 --> 03:04:34.099
[SPEAKER_74]: And so we need to be there at the rally.

03:04:34.119 --> 03:04:35.601
[SPEAKER_74]: We need to be there on the line with you.

03:04:35.641 --> 03:04:38.404
[SPEAKER_74]: We didn't make sure that if we own this

03:04:39.447 --> 03:04:41.049
[SPEAKER_74]: We need to make sure it's right for our kids.

03:04:41.529 --> 03:04:42.751
[SPEAKER_74]: So thank you and your work.

03:04:43.291 --> 03:04:46.195
[SPEAKER_74]: And we will win this one together.

03:04:48.257 --> 03:04:49.419
[SPEAKER_76]: Thank you, Mr. McOsker.

03:04:49.479 --> 03:04:50.500
[SPEAKER_76]: Council Member Padilla.

03:04:52.542 --> 03:04:57.928
[SPEAKER_59]: Thank you, Council Member Hernandez and Sotomayor Martinez for bringing all of our partners from education here.

03:04:57.988 --> 03:05:07.159
[SPEAKER_59]: You know, my immediate reaction when I found out that you guys are once again in this position is like, really, again?

03:05:07.274 --> 03:05:22.267
[SPEAKER_59]: I feel like almost every other year we are in a position where we have to push and hit the streets to get some serious attention related to what educators and those who support our educators on the campus deserve.

03:05:23.610 --> 03:05:27.038
[SPEAKER_59]: I can't believe we're still trying to convince

03:05:28.064 --> 03:05:43.448
[SPEAKER_59]: the board and those who are in charge of the school district, that community schools are important, that workforce development is important, that the SEIU members who do all of the extra work also should not have their healthcare cut.

03:05:43.908 --> 03:05:56.788
[SPEAKER_59]: I was at a public library at an event that I hosted and I had SEIU members wearing their t-shirts proudly enjoying my event and they told me that this was happening because I continue to talk to the people that are your members because they live in my district.

03:05:56.768 --> 03:05:59.431
[SPEAKER_59]: Can you imagine if they didn't have their healthcare?

