03:57:20.995 --> 03:57:21.836
[SPEAKER_65]: Hi, good afternoon.

03:57:21.916 --> 03:57:22.397
[SPEAKER_65]: Thank you.

03:57:23.038 --> 03:57:34.133
[SPEAKER_65]: So just to kind of set the table, colleagues, no one has been a bigger advocate from day one about working to get into compliance with our alliance agreement.

03:57:34.614 --> 03:57:45.729
[SPEAKER_65]: There have been many obstructions and detours and avoidance of that, but I'm glad to see that we are here now actively working on fulfilling that compliance.

03:57:45.769 --> 03:57:49.855
[SPEAKER_65]: However, I did have questions regarding the time-limited subsidies.

03:57:50.020 --> 03:57:58.768
[SPEAKER_65]: So, one of the items, I want to better understand in terms of the placement of the individuals in TLS.

03:57:59.369 --> 03:58:09.778
[SPEAKER_65]: Now, many people in the public don't understand, so we have a combination of housing solutions that we are offering to help address the unhoused population.

03:58:10.979 --> 03:58:18.306
[SPEAKER_65]: We have the interim housing, we have the permanent supportive, both have

03:58:18.657 --> 03:58:24.104
[SPEAKER_65]: rather robust support case management systems.

03:58:24.785 --> 03:58:33.936
[SPEAKER_65]: But when it comes to TLS, you're talking about a broad distribution of how people are placed.

03:58:33.956 --> 03:58:40.665
[SPEAKER_65]: Can you just explain for the public and for those that may not be aware how TLS is implemented?

03:58:45.640 --> 03:58:47.042
[SPEAKER_13]: Good afternoon Councilmembers.

03:58:47.062 --> 03:58:49.186
[SPEAKER_13]: Nathaniel Regao, Deputy Chief Program Officer at LAHSA.

03:58:49.686 --> 03:58:55.075
[SPEAKER_13]: So this is a question specifically about the services provided or how or where people are housed?

03:58:55.095 --> 03:59:02.086
[SPEAKER_65]: How are individuals selected to participate in TLS and what is the corresponding case management approach?

03:59:02.186 --> 03:59:06.012
[SPEAKER_65]: Because so just to frame it.

03:59:06.650 --> 03:59:18.634
[SPEAKER_65]: When we have an interim housing location, like what I have in Sylmar, we have on-site case management people that are assigned to helping to address the circumstances and needs of the individuals.

03:59:18.715 --> 03:59:19.877
[SPEAKER_65]: in those facilities.

03:59:20.578 --> 03:59:34.859
[SPEAKER_65]: When we talk about permanent supportive housing, that is even, frankly, even more so in terms of the depth of services, the level of services that those individuals are securing.

03:59:34.899 --> 03:59:39.306
[SPEAKER_65]: Now, we have a very dynamic

03:59:40.028 --> 03:59:45.514
[SPEAKER_65]: circumstance with the level of acuity that many of the individuals that we are placing into housing have.

03:59:46.115 --> 04:00:03.994
[SPEAKER_65]: We have a responsibility to attempt, and I recognize the challenge with that, attempt the proper placement with individuals should they be perhaps experiencing severe mental health or substance use disorder issues in coordination with the county.

04:00:04.565 --> 04:00:10.697
[SPEAKER_65]: What I wanted to better understand in terms of the TLS is what is the level of acuity of the individuals?

04:00:10.757 --> 04:00:19.955
[SPEAKER_65]: What is the level of case management and support services that are going to be offered to these individuals that are going to be really assessed and surveyed for efficacy?

04:00:20.576 --> 04:00:25.746
[SPEAKER_65]: And the reason why is because these individuals are not all placed in one location.

04:00:26.148 --> 04:00:26.449
[SPEAKER_65]: Right?

04:00:26.930 --> 04:00:32.020
[SPEAKER_65]: So I just want to better understand how that is going to be addressed.

04:00:33.122 --> 04:00:37.811
[SPEAKER_65]: How are you, how are those individuals, on what basis are individuals being selected?

04:00:37.871 --> 04:00:39.013
[SPEAKER_65]: What is the procedure?

04:00:39.514 --> 04:00:41.338
[SPEAKER_65]: So that, because.

04:00:41.318 --> 04:00:52.631
[SPEAKER_65]: And I'll allow, I want to give you the opportunity to explain how people are selected, how locations are determined, what are the, how does TLS work?

04:00:52.651 --> 04:01:10.212
[SPEAKER_65]: And I think it's important for everyone to understand how TLS works, how we are going to be measuring the results of it, but more importantly, how do you ensure the placement of individuals and not disrupting perhaps if they're in a residential,

04:01:11.002 --> 04:01:15.706
[SPEAKER_65]: or which they will be in a residential unit, or what have you, depending on the circumstances.

04:01:18.008 --> 04:01:21.271
[SPEAKER_65]: How we mitigate any possible risk about.

04:01:23.193 --> 04:01:23.553
[SPEAKER_65]: Got it.

04:01:23.573 --> 04:01:24.954
[SPEAKER_65]: Go ahead.

04:01:24.974 --> 04:01:25.294
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you.

04:01:25.334 --> 04:01:28.537
[SPEAKER_20]: Sophia Rice, Chief Program Officer at LAHSA.

04:01:28.577 --> 04:01:29.998
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you for the questions.

04:01:30.179 --> 04:01:41.008
[SPEAKER_20]: I think a lot of what you're speaking to gets to the reasons for some of the strengthening of the new City Alliance TLS program that we've worked on.

04:01:42.389 --> 04:01:50.723
[SPEAKER_20]: The sort of beauty of the TLS design in general is that it does help encourage throughput in the system.

04:01:50.963 --> 04:02:04.186
[SPEAKER_20]: So we are, for the city TLS program, the new TLS program, it will prioritize individuals who are in city-funded interim housing who have stayed for a long time, so.

04:02:04.707 --> 04:02:06.029
[SPEAKER_20]: Stabilized.

04:02:06.049 --> 04:02:06.169
[SPEAKER_20]: Right.

04:02:06.942 --> 04:02:27.111
[SPEAKER_20]: They've been in interim housing for 12 months or more at first and really prioritizing helping to get people into a TLS slot so that they can have the support to be able to move through the TLS program and move into a more permanent housing.

04:02:27.631 --> 04:02:33.901
[SPEAKER_20]: Whether that be permanent supportive housing or they take over the rent or an affordable unit.

04:02:33.921 --> 04:02:42.775
[SPEAKER_20]: So part of the redesign for the new city TLS program is to actually call out those three separate tracks.

04:02:43.556 --> 04:02:45.960
[SPEAKER_20]: So when people enter the TLS program,

04:02:45.940 --> 04:02:49.985
[SPEAKER_20]: They'll be working with a variety of different supports.

04:02:50.385 --> 04:03:06.464
[SPEAKER_20]: They'll be assessed with a new assessment that we're developing with the help of GPL to really be able to designate where we think that people will sort of complete the program in which path.

04:03:06.505 --> 04:03:07.746
[SPEAKER_20]: So that's either

04:03:07.726 --> 04:03:21.888
[SPEAKER_20]: You know, you're somebody who can get employment support and you can grow your income and then you're able to take over your rent, whether that be a lease in place where you were with TLS or whether you move into a unit that maybe is more affordable or a roommate situation or what have you.

04:03:22.549 --> 04:03:27.777
[SPEAKER_20]: You also have people who we know are on fixed income, they may not need

04:03:27.925 --> 04:03:32.169
[SPEAKER_20]: significant support, like an intensive case management service.

04:03:32.809 --> 04:03:34.771
[SPEAKER_20]: But we know that their income is going to be limited.

04:03:34.831 --> 04:03:39.375
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's going to be sort of prohibitive for them to be able to transition out of TLS.

04:03:39.796 --> 04:03:46.182
[SPEAKER_20]: And so the work will be more geared towards getting them on a lot of wait lists for affordable housing throughout LA County.

04:03:46.202 --> 04:03:51.987
[SPEAKER_20]: There's sort of a web of different wait lists to navigate, so support there.

04:03:52.648 --> 04:03:57.612
[SPEAKER_20]: And then there are other people who will need additional supports in the permanent supportive housing placement and sort

04:03:57.828 --> 04:03:59.290
[SPEAKER_20]: wrapping around the services for them.

04:03:59.390 --> 04:04:09.604
[SPEAKER_20]: So the goal is really to move people out of interim housing, to be able to also free up slots in interim housing beds, which is great.

04:04:09.624 --> 04:04:10.265
[SPEAKER_20]: We all want that.

04:04:10.906 --> 04:04:21.381
[SPEAKER_20]: And then be able to move people into TLS, where we can get a better idea of really what their needs are and be able to help them through the system and move into a more permanent placement.

04:04:22.282 --> 04:04:26.468
[SPEAKER_65]: So my question is, obviously, now that the county has pulled out of LAHSA,

04:04:27.055 --> 04:04:31.160
[SPEAKER_65]: and the city is the primary source of funding.

04:04:32.362 --> 04:04:39.592
[SPEAKER_65]: In terms of the individuals that are in interim or that could be utilized for TLS, will they be exclusively LA City?

04:04:40.753 --> 04:04:46.641
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes, they are current individuals who are staying at a city-funded interim housing.

04:04:46.741 --> 04:04:49.465
[SPEAKER_20]: That is who is being moved into a new program.

04:04:49.485 --> 04:04:56.995
[SPEAKER_65]: And then who is determining the acuity level or the preparedness of these individuals to be able to matriculate into TLS?

04:04:59.101 --> 04:05:06.214
[SPEAKER_13]: So it depends on how long the participant has stayed in their interim housing.

04:05:06.615 --> 04:05:13.648
[SPEAKER_13]: Interim housing providers should be doing assessments for permanent supportive housing need within 90 days of entering the shelter.

04:05:14.249 --> 04:05:17.515
[SPEAKER_13]: Since we're prioritizing long stayers, they will have likely

04:05:17.647 --> 04:05:36.972
[SPEAKER_13]: They should have certainly been assessed before we are linking them to TLS as Sophia mentioned we are also Going to be doing an additional assessment once folks move into their TLS placement because once folks get into an apartment Out of shelter that can be more chaotic of an environment in your own apartment where you can close the door and lock it

04:05:37.357 --> 04:05:50.250
[SPEAKER_13]: Folks tend to stabilize and so we want to be able to continue to assess need so that we're not Putting people on a track to permit supportive housing that is not necessarily really what they need So the beauty of TLS is that allows us to continue that assessment?

04:05:50.270 --> 04:05:54.420
[SPEAKER_13]: So that we're not utilizing high-cost resources for folks who don't truly need those

04:05:55.497 --> 04:06:01.830
[SPEAKER_20]: to meet the, they don't need to meet the threshold for PSH to be able to move into the TLS program.

04:06:01.870 --> 04:06:03.213
[SPEAKER_20]: That's something that we would determine.

04:06:05.057 --> 04:06:07.862
[SPEAKER_20]: And really could be a mix and also circumstances change for people.

04:06:07.882 --> 04:06:09.726
[SPEAKER_20]: That's why the, you know, assessments are ongoing.

04:06:09.892 --> 04:06:12.455
[SPEAKER_65]: And what is the prioritization around families?

04:06:12.796 --> 04:06:18.103
[SPEAKER_65]: There's been a lot of conversations with respect to the homeless response that we've had in this city.

04:06:18.844 --> 04:06:25.433
[SPEAKER_65]: And the biggest failure has been around the lack of options for a number of families.

04:06:26.755 --> 04:06:31.461
[SPEAKER_65]: What is the opportunity with TLS to help address that population?

04:06:31.930 --> 04:06:35.697
[SPEAKER_13]: So families can be eligible for this project.

04:06:36.158 --> 04:06:45.795
[SPEAKER_13]: At this point, the rate for each slot has been designed for single individuals because families tend to need larger units, which come with a larger rental cost.

04:06:45.815 --> 04:06:50.243
[SPEAKER_13]: So it would impact overall either the need for potential additional investment if we have

04:06:50.223 --> 04:06:57.596
[SPEAKER_13]: a large number of families that cost more per person or per household, or it would cut down on the number of households we could serve.

04:06:58.258 --> 04:07:05.411
[SPEAKER_13]: So the initial design was primarily based on serving individuals, but we have the capacity to serve families.

04:07:05.431 --> 04:07:13.986
[SPEAKER_65]: So is this just to get us to our minimum, the minimum threshold of what we need to fulfill in order to achieve our alliance goals?

04:07:14.506 --> 04:07:21.293
[SPEAKER_13]: It's funded for 2,000 slots at the individual rate, correct.

04:07:21.313 --> 04:07:28.541
[SPEAKER_65]: OK. What solutions are being brought forward to address what is a growing circumstance of a number of families?

04:07:29.142 --> 04:07:40.834
[SPEAKER_65]: And what is the estimated cost of helping to, like, you know, and I don't even know what the numbers are in terms of families right now.

04:07:42.029 --> 04:07:46.140
[SPEAKER_65]: It's one of the most critical areas that we can address.

04:07:46.801 --> 04:07:57.068
[SPEAKER_65]: And when we talk about a per unit cost, and I understand what you're saying, but at the same time, depending upon where they go in the city, it actually might be the same.

04:07:57.503 --> 04:07:58.484
[SPEAKER_65]: level of subsidy.

04:07:59.025 --> 04:08:03.430
[SPEAKER_65]: So has that been evaluated to help address that critical population?

04:08:04.351 --> 04:08:06.433
[SPEAKER_65]: Because we've got a lot of families.

04:08:06.453 --> 04:08:08.135
[SPEAKER_65]: You've got a lot of families in Skid Row.

04:08:08.155 --> 04:08:10.438
[SPEAKER_65]: You've got a lot of families all over the city that are struggling.

04:08:10.478 --> 04:08:19.428
[SPEAKER_65]: And so how are we, or how are you, identifying pathways to help address that population need?

04:08:19.448 --> 04:08:20.109
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah.

04:08:20.129 --> 04:08:25.755
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, one thing I'll say is just that part of the redesign for this program as well is

04:08:26.326 --> 04:08:37.859
[SPEAKER_20]: Centralizing the housing location in collaboration with Lhasa, but hopefully with our our partners at home Inc. Who have a lot of experience in developing?

04:08:38.980 --> 04:08:50.393
[SPEAKER_20]: you know landlord connections and and affordable housing resources and so one of the benefits to centralizing those services that it also allows home and

04:08:50.373 --> 04:08:58.290
[SPEAKER_20]: to really build a large pool of affordable resources across the city.

04:08:58.658 --> 04:09:04.026
[SPEAKER_20]: In my former life, I was at Brilliant Corners overseeing the Flexible Housing Subsidy Pool, if anybody knows that program.

04:09:04.067 --> 04:09:06.050
[SPEAKER_20]: And we did a lot of housing location and acquisition.

04:09:06.090 --> 04:09:23.417
[SPEAKER_20]: And one thing that was, services are different than home, but they're somewhat the same, in that a lot of what we found is that when you make connections with landlord partners, usually we're talking about studios and one bedrooms or SROs.

04:09:23.515 --> 04:09:33.370
[SPEAKER_20]: But once you make those connections, you often have access to a whole portfolio, once you build that relationship, of other unit sizes.

04:09:33.911 --> 04:09:35.874
[SPEAKER_20]: So two bedrooms and even some three bedrooms.

04:09:35.894 --> 04:09:41.383
[SPEAKER_20]: And to your point, on the whole, those bigger units are going to be more costly, but not always.

04:09:42.064 --> 04:09:42.885
[SPEAKER_20]: Not always the case.

04:09:42.945 --> 04:09:47.532
[SPEAKER_20]: And especially if you have built those good relationships with the property providers and are

04:09:47.512 --> 04:09:55.166
[SPEAKER_20]: for rent reasonableness and working very diligently with a centralized provider like HOME to negotiate those rents to affordability.

04:09:55.447 --> 04:10:02.319
[SPEAKER_20]: So, you know, I don't want to give the impression that families cannot be included in the TLS program.

04:10:03.081 --> 04:10:03.201
[SPEAKER_65]: Okay.

04:10:03.722 --> 04:10:09.773
[SPEAKER_65]: And then just in terms of the queuing of those that become eligible for the TLS, I just want to be clear.

04:10:09.753 --> 04:10:21.532
[SPEAKER_65]: and just to affirm that, because you've got a lot of individuals that have been in the interim for an extended period of time waiting for that opportunity to matriculate out.

04:10:22.554 --> 04:10:28.643
[SPEAKER_65]: How is the queuing, for lack of a better word, in terms of the prioritization, how is that going to work?

04:10:29.004 --> 04:10:30.126
[SPEAKER_65]: Who's determining that?

04:10:30.647 --> 04:10:35.895
[SPEAKER_65]: Is it based on any one particular program or is it based on who's been,

04:10:35.875 --> 04:10:38.338
[SPEAKER_65]: placed in that interim solution the longest?

04:10:38.418 --> 04:10:43.124
[SPEAKER_65]: Is it you kind of have first in, kind of first out dynamic?

04:10:43.364 --> 04:10:44.766
[SPEAKER_65]: What's the procedure?

04:10:46.027 --> 04:10:54.878
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, so the prioritization criteria for participants will be based on longer stares in interim housing and dependent on length of time.

04:10:55.598 --> 04:11:01.225
[SPEAKER_20]: We also have, we're building out sort of a ramp up schedule of providers because

04:11:01.677 --> 04:11:10.589
[SPEAKER_20]: You know, we sort of understand that we're working at a very fast pace right now because of the sort of deadline with getting leased up and the funding.

04:11:11.070 --> 04:11:21.745
[SPEAKER_20]: And so we are proposing to ramp up the slots based on providers who, you know,

04:11:22.197 --> 04:11:32.630
[SPEAKER_20]: already have capacity because, you know, at the same time as we're ramping up the Alliance program, we're also ramping down some TLS programs, as you mentioned, related to some of the funding changes.

04:11:33.351 --> 04:11:49.572
[SPEAKER_20]: And so we wanted to make sure that the initial tranche of service providers that were able to work with folks in the TLS program were ones that already had the capacity, were already working with Home Inc. as a fiscal agent, and so we're familiar with those processes.

04:11:49.788 --> 04:11:53.995
[SPEAKER_20]: We'll be looking at those couple of providers for this first initial push.

04:11:54.836 --> 04:11:58.662
[SPEAKER_20]: And so the prioritization will be for long stares and intramuscular.

04:11:58.682 --> 04:12:10.822
[SPEAKER_65]: So, you know, I just wanted to, I've asked multiple times from LASA about what is the methodology to evaluate the service providers that are actually doing that case management and monitoring.

04:12:10.842 --> 04:12:14.007
[SPEAKER_65]: And we've seen, you know, had a few black eyes on this.

04:12:14.341 --> 04:12:30.697
[SPEAKER_65]: And when you have TLS and you enter into that, it becomes even more critical that you have reputable agencies engaged in that work to monitor because you could potentially undermine the ability to continue to sustain this work.

04:12:30.717 --> 04:12:32.318
[SPEAKER_65]: It's like any other facility.

04:12:32.779 --> 04:12:40.686
[SPEAKER_65]: If it fails to perform or it becomes a nuisance or becomes a bigger problem, you're going to have more resistance from people willing to participate.

04:12:41.341 --> 04:12:58.692
[SPEAKER_20]: And part of the RFP process for this particular program was also a high-weighted scoring for providers that were providing currently either a TLS program through LASA or a very similar program, and we looked

04:12:58.672 --> 04:13:15.263
[SPEAKER_20]: very closely at their key performance indicators to ensure that they were scoring very high on just the basics of data quality, so entering in their data, but also that they were able to help people who were trying to grow their income,

04:13:15.243 --> 04:13:18.209
[SPEAKER_20]: transitioning people to PSH who are qualified quickly.

04:13:18.249 --> 04:13:20.292
[SPEAKER_20]: So that was very forefront of mind.

04:13:20.653 --> 04:13:33.818
[SPEAKER_20]: And then the other thing I'll say is that around the redesign, part of what we're working on currently is building out even better and easier to use monitoring tools for doing exactly that.

04:13:33.898 --> 04:13:36.002
[SPEAKER_20]: So really, again,

04:13:36.505 --> 04:13:42.016
[SPEAKER_20]: Making sure that people are clearly designated on one of these three paths, which we know can change over time.

04:13:42.137 --> 04:13:43.399
[SPEAKER_20]: There's the flexibility.

04:13:43.740 --> 04:13:51.616
[SPEAKER_20]: But also then being able to assess how well folks are able to move through the program and successfully transition out.

04:13:51.636 --> 04:13:53.620
[SPEAKER_20]: So it's a very good point.

04:13:53.600 --> 04:13:54.221
[SPEAKER_65]: Okay.

04:13:54.241 --> 04:14:13.735
[SPEAKER_65]: Well, again, I just wanted to better understand in terms of procedure, making sure that the acuity levels of the individuals that we're talking about aren't, that we're not having a circumstance where in the effort to try and accelerate those placements of individuals or perhaps move them from the street,

04:14:14.710 --> 04:14:23.221
[SPEAKER_65]: If you do it too quickly, then you're setting yourself up for failure and a failure of the whole effort.

04:14:23.702 --> 04:14:31.172
[SPEAKER_65]: And so I wanted to better understand procedurally how that was going to happen, because this is something that I know we'll all be monitoring very closely.

04:14:31.232 --> 04:14:42.186
[SPEAKER_65]: It's critically important, not just because we want to be in compliance with the alliance agreement, but it shouldn't be an accelerator to help

04:14:42.335 --> 04:14:50.271
[SPEAKER_65]: advance certain placements of individuals that perhaps are not prepared to be living in that type of circumstance.

04:14:50.291 --> 04:14:58.167
[SPEAKER_65]: And more importantly, I really want to make sure that what we can do going forward is to maximize the opportunities for us to also aid families

04:14:58.147 --> 04:15:04.699
[SPEAKER_65]: who are frankly just part of that economic shortfall of being able to sustain themselves.

04:15:04.759 --> 04:15:11.352
[SPEAKER_65]: And so the acuity levels are really born out of economics, which is not all the other circumstances generally.

04:15:11.733 --> 04:15:15.700
[SPEAKER_65]: And so to the extent that we can help support

04:15:16.456 --> 04:15:19.581
[SPEAKER_65]: That population is critically important.

04:15:19.962 --> 04:15:21.965
[SPEAKER_20]: And I think we've seen a huge need for that.

04:15:22.225 --> 04:15:38.110
[SPEAKER_20]: I think the current TLS program that is ramping down is very strong and has had strong outcomes, but we also were able to see that there were gaps there and really be thoughtful about designing this new program to be in response to some of those gaps.

04:15:38.427 --> 04:15:50.985
[SPEAKER_20]: So there are a couple other things I'll just very quickly say that I think, you know, would be helpful is that, again, you know, it'll be the longest stayers that have been more stabilized in interim housing for 12 months or more initially.

04:15:51.025 --> 04:15:56.233
[SPEAKER_20]: And then also the TLS case management support that they'll be getting.

04:15:56.669 --> 04:15:58.090
[SPEAKER_20]: It's very intensive.

04:15:58.331 --> 04:16:01.093
[SPEAKER_20]: It's more intensive at the beginning of the program.

04:16:01.173 --> 04:16:24.956
[SPEAKER_20]: So also recognizing that as people are moving into a new location and moving out of interim housing that we really need to ensure that all of that wraparound support is really front loaded so that we can determine what their needs are and help to really keep them stabilized and put them on the right path to be able to transition out, whether that's at 24 months, which is the goal of the program is 24 months or less, or sooner for some people.

04:16:25.017 --> 04:16:26.558
[SPEAKER_20]: There are some people who really need

04:16:26.842 --> 04:16:36.413
[SPEAKER_20]: you know, a couple of really intensive months, and then are able to sort of get back on their feet or go to a different housing setting.

04:16:37.474 --> 04:16:37.574
[SPEAKER_20]: Okay.

04:16:37.594 --> 04:16:38.215
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you very much.

04:16:39.516 --> 04:16:43.841
[SPEAKER_76]: Thank you, Councilmember Rodriguez, and thank you all for answering the questions.

04:16:43.901 --> 04:16:52.690
[SPEAKER_76]: I think there's a lot of excitement that this program is getting refined and redesigned, and certainly the issues that Councilmember Rodriguez raised are important.

04:16:53.131 --> 04:16:56.815
[SPEAKER_76]: And also, on the other side of that coin, you know, just I can say,

04:16:57.807 --> 04:17:01.891
[SPEAKER_76]: In my bridge home shelter now, I have people who get up and go to work every day.

04:17:02.292 --> 04:17:02.772
[SPEAKER_20]: Absolutely.

04:17:03.112 --> 04:17:06.676
[SPEAKER_76]: So they don't need to stay there for nine months or a year or whatever.

04:17:07.036 --> 04:17:13.763
