04:25:43.408 --> 04:25:59.768
[SPEAKER_13]: The case ratio is 1 to 20, which is also comparable at not only the rate, but the payment rate, but also the case ratio rate is comparable to what the intensive case management services through the county are.

04:25:59.748 --> 04:26:08.985
[SPEAKER_13]: Also, I think it's important to note that in permanent supportive housing, there are also tenant-based permanent supportive housing, meaning scattered sites where folks are in private apartments.

04:26:09.426 --> 04:26:19.545
[SPEAKER_13]: So this work is done all the time currently across the nation and here in Los Angeles for permanent supportive housing as well as in the time-limited subsidies.

04:26:19.525 --> 04:26:41.584
[SPEAKER_13]: So, as Sophia pointed out earlier, we have designed the program so that there is more intensive services when folks initially move in, so that we are wrapping folks with services as they move in in that transition, which can be the most tumultuous point for a participant, where they're coming out of a shelter that they, an environment that they know, they're moving into

04:26:41.851 --> 04:26:45.557
[SPEAKER_13]: an apartment potentially for the first time in a long time where they've lived on their own.

04:26:46.017 --> 04:26:55.732
[SPEAKER_13]: So we wrap services around for that initial period more intensively than they may necessarily need throughout their stay in the time limit subsidy.

04:26:56.714 --> 04:27:00.720
[SPEAKER_13]: The expectations in terms of the case managers in the TLS.

04:27:01.004 --> 04:27:05.109
[SPEAKER_13]: is that they're also accessing additional services available in the community.

04:27:05.269 --> 04:27:29.458
[SPEAKER_13]: So if a participant has mental health needs, that they are ensuring that they're connected with the Department of Mental Health for outpatient services at various levels, whether that's the full service partnership, which is a really high intensive level of wraparound services provided by the Department of Mental Health, or just a more standard connection to an outpatient clinic where folks can go in for their medication and therapy services.

04:27:29.438 --> 04:27:30.600
[SPEAKER_13]: on a scheduled basis.

04:27:31.060 --> 04:27:38.650
[SPEAKER_13]: But the expectation is that those case managers in TLS are ensuring that those connections are made both for physical health, mental health, and substance use.

04:27:39.351 --> 04:27:44.758
[SPEAKER_13]: So again, connection with substance abuse prevention and control for folks who have substance use issues.

04:27:45.800 --> 04:27:53.590
[SPEAKER_13]: So regardless of their needs, whether it's employment programs for folks who may already be working but may need to

04:27:53.570 --> 04:28:00.083
[SPEAKER_13]: increase their income, have capacity to work but are not yet, we're working to make sure that they're connected to those resources.

04:28:00.123 --> 04:28:06.375
[SPEAKER_13]: For folks who have challenges with their mental health, they will be making sure that they're connected to the Department of Mental Health for those services.

04:28:07.137 --> 04:28:13.249
[SPEAKER_13]: For physical health, making sure that they're connected to a local clinic, an FQHC or a DHS provided clinic.

04:28:13.921 --> 04:28:41.717
[SPEAKER_13]: And similarly for mental health that they're connected with a low Substance use services that are connected with a local substance abuse provider So the goal is to wrap those services around intensively at the beginning and then based on their service need Potentially taper off because they're getting the connection with the demand of the mental health provider getting additional case management through there That then also frees up some services for them as a new person comes in to really wrap around that new person

04:28:42.068 --> 04:28:48.698
[SPEAKER_13]: So there's a blend of services based on the individual needs of the participant.

04:28:48.719 --> 04:29:09.291
[SPEAKER_20]: The only other thing I would add to it, and I agree with what Nathaniel said, but also part of the thinking behind the redesign in being able to sort of assess individuals for these three tracks is that it also helps document that and, you know, building out tools that make that easier for our providers so that

04:29:09.271 --> 04:29:11.935
[SPEAKER_20]: They're also able to staff around that.

04:29:12.015 --> 04:29:13.358
[SPEAKER_20]: Of course, again, it's flexible.

04:29:13.778 --> 04:29:16.443
[SPEAKER_20]: Things change with an individual depending on what's going on with them.

04:29:16.763 --> 04:29:24.816
[SPEAKER_20]: But the provider organizations are going to be able to craft caseloads for their case managers that allow them to have the capacity

04:29:24.796 --> 04:29:31.748
[SPEAKER_20]: to support with more of their time individuals who have more of that acute need, especially initially.

04:29:32.329 --> 04:29:36.737
[SPEAKER_20]: And then they might have individuals who need other types of support, like we said, applying for waiting lists.

04:29:36.757 --> 04:29:39.482
[SPEAKER_20]: But it's not as much of that high acuity need.

04:29:39.522 --> 04:29:49.099
[SPEAKER_20]: So they'll be able to have a mixed caseload in a way that sort of works to be able to create that capacity that I think gets at what you're talking about.

04:29:49.433 --> 04:30:08.826
