[SPEAKER_39]: The key to helping someone survive a choking incident is being able to immediately recognize the signs they are in trouble.

05:37:15.035 --> 05:37:17.800
[SPEAKER_39]: These are the most common signs someone is choking.

05:37:18.877 --> 05:37:21.841
[SPEAKER_39]: One or both of their hands clutched to the throat.

05:37:22.581 --> 05:37:24.804
[SPEAKER_39]: Look of panic, shock, or confusion.

05:37:25.565 --> 05:37:28.088
[SPEAKER_39]: Inability to talk or cough.

05:37:28.108 --> 05:37:30.331
[SPEAKER_39]: Color changing to blue or gray.

05:37:31.252 --> 05:37:35.317
[SPEAKER_39]: If the person can cough forcefully, encourage them to keep coughing.

05:37:35.978 --> 05:37:42.325
[SPEAKER_39]: If the person cannot cough or talk, you need to quickly take action and perform abdominal thrusts.

05:37:43.226 --> 05:37:48.613
[SPEAKER_39]: For an adult, stand behind the person with one foot slightly in front of the other for balance.

05:37:48.897 --> 05:37:52.823
[SPEAKER_39]: Wrap your arms around the waist and tip the person forward slightly.

05:37:53.925 --> 05:37:56.869
[SPEAKER_39]: Make a fist and put it just above the person's navel.

05:37:57.831 --> 05:38:05.482
[SPEAKER_39]: Grasp your fist with your other hand and press it into their stomach with a quick upward thrust, as if you're trying to lift the person up.

05:38:06.484 --> 05:38:10.450
[SPEAKER_39]: Give five abdominal thrusts, then check if the blockage is cleared.

05:38:10.818 --> 05:38:12.901
[SPEAKER_39]: If it is not cleared, repeat as needed.

05:38:13.541 --> 05:38:19.749
[SPEAKER_39]: If the person is pregnant or you cannot get your arms around their stomach, give chest thrust instead.

05:38:20.390 --> 05:38:22.492
[SPEAKER_39]: Put your hands at the base of the breastbone.

05:38:22.873 --> 05:38:25.396
[SPEAKER_39]: Press hard into the chest with a quick thrust.

05:38:26.057 --> 05:38:29.281
[SPEAKER_39]: Perform five thrusts and check if the blockage is cleared.

05:38:32.344 --> 05:38:38.732
[SPEAKER_39]: If the person becomes unconscious, you will need to begin CPR and contact 911.

