05:49:06.158 --> 05:49:07.720
[SPEAKER_60]: Thank you, Mr. President.

05:49:07.820 --> 05:49:21.977
[SPEAKER_60]: Colleagues, before we adjourn today, I'd like to take a moment to honor the life of a remarkable young woman from right here in Los Angeles, Alyssa Williams, known to everyone who loved her as Pepper.

05:49:22.938 --> 05:49:25.521
[SPEAKER_60]: Pepper was born and raised in Los Angeles County.

05:49:25.561 --> 05:49:27.584
[SPEAKER_60]: She was definitely one of ours.

05:49:28.204 --> 05:49:32.109
[SPEAKER_60]: Those who knew her remember her most for her radiant smile and warmth.

05:49:32.630 --> 05:49:34.512
[SPEAKER_60]: She bought into every room she entered.

05:49:35.015 --> 05:49:45.249
[SPEAKER_60]: She was a free spirit who lived life on her own terms, someone who loved outdoors, surfing, running, cooking, and exploring farmers markets.

05:49:45.729 --> 05:49:52.678
[SPEAKER_60]: She had an extraordinary gift for showing up for people and creating meaningful connections wherever she went.

05:49:53.359 --> 05:49:55.803
[SPEAKER_60]: Pepper had deep roots in the community.

05:49:56.283 --> 05:49:59.908
[SPEAKER_60]: She treasured her Saturday mornings with her Peace for Kids family.

05:50:00.344 --> 05:50:05.351
[SPEAKER_60]: where she built a lifetime of memories alongside Zad, Diane, and so many others.

05:50:06.192 --> 05:50:12.841
[SPEAKER_60]: And in the community she found at the Salvation Army in Santa Monica, she didn't just find a program.

05:50:14.183 --> 05:50:17.548
[SPEAKER_60]: She found a family with Nicole Lim, Anthony, and many more.

05:50:18.169 --> 05:50:24.057
[SPEAKER_60]: The bonds she formed there were real, lasting, and a testament to the kind of person she was.

05:50:24.408 --> 05:50:28.975
[SPEAKER_60]: Someone who could walk into any space and make it feel like home for everyone around her.

05:50:29.676 --> 05:50:37.870
[SPEAKER_60]: A graduate of Morningside High in Inglewood, Pepper's path was shaped by experiences that too many Angelenos know firsthand.

05:50:38.511 --> 05:50:39.893
[SPEAKER_60]: She faced homelessness.

05:50:40.394 --> 05:50:44.420
[SPEAKER_60]: She navigated struggles that our city is grappling with every single day.

05:50:45.161 --> 05:50:51.732
[SPEAKER_60]: And rather than let those experience define her as a victim, she let them define her as someone with a mission.

05:50:52.252 --> 05:51:03.492
[SPEAKER_60]: She found her calling in helping others heal, pursuing her certification as a drug and alcohol wellness counselor, not just as a career, but as a commitment.

05:51:04.333 --> 05:51:08.440
[SPEAKER_60]: She wanted to be for others as she wanted people to be for her.

05:51:09.141 --> 05:51:14.631
[SPEAKER_60]: She was too close to finishing, and she pursued that goal with unwavering dedication.

05:51:14.932 --> 05:51:16.374
[SPEAKER_60]: because that was just Pepper.

05:51:16.934 --> 05:51:29.969
[SPEAKER_60]: Her story is a reminder that everyone that has static, every name on a housing list, every name navigating our system, there's a full human being with gifts to give and love to share.

05:51:30.650 --> 05:51:36.116
[SPEAKER_60]: Colleagues, I want to speak to something that makes Pepper's story particularly powerful.

05:51:37.838 --> 05:51:42.643
[SPEAKER_60]: She carried real hardship, amount that seemed deeply unfair to those who loved her.

05:51:42.978 --> 05:51:49.605
[SPEAKER_60]: She faced struggles that would have been broken so many, as do many who have experienced the foster care system.

05:51:50.306 --> 05:52:01.378
[SPEAKER_60]: And yet in the midst of it all, Pepper chose to be a light, not because life had been simple or kind to her, but in spite of the fact that it hadn't.

05:52:01.398 --> 05:52:04.522
[SPEAKER_60]: She didn't wait until things were perfect to show up with a smile.

05:52:04.682 --> 05:52:10.669
[SPEAKER_60]: She didn't wait until her burdens were lifted before she helped carry someone else's.

05:52:10.689 --> 05:52:12.951
[SPEAKER_60]: That's a rare and extraordinary quality.

05:52:13.387 --> 05:52:17.571
[SPEAKER_60]: The people around her didn't just appreciate her, they were charged by her.

05:52:18.132 --> 05:52:27.963
[SPEAKER_60]: She left an imprint on every life she touched, not because her path was without struggle, but because she refused to let that struggle dim what she had to give.

05:52:29.164 --> 05:52:33.388
[SPEAKER_60]: In the darkness, Pepper was a light, and she brought that light with her everywhere she went.

05:52:34.109 --> 05:52:39.495
[SPEAKER_60]: She is survived by her siblings, Shana, Floyd, Yvette, and Shonda.

05:52:39.678 --> 05:52:47.207
[SPEAKER_60]: and by her extended family, including Clements, Zavi, Olivia, Lex, Tony, Kenisha, and Kendra.

05:52:48.168 --> 05:52:53.294
[SPEAKER_60]: She will be deeply missed, but she will be carried forward in the hearts of everyone she touched.

05:52:55.557 --> 05:53:02.225
[SPEAKER_60]: I ask for this adjournment in memory and in love for Alyssa Pepper-Williams.

05:53:02.245 --> 05:53:02.545
